animal.description: The name Maverick has the meaning of independent and bursting with spirit. Pasadena Humane's Maverick was brought in by an owner who simply didn't have the time or energy to deal with the playful spirit he has! Maverick is reported to play hard and is full of energy. Here at the shelter, Maverick was confused and becsme anxious, although with calm and consistent interaction with our staff, a more trusting dog is begining to emerge. At a youthful 2 years of age, Maverick still has a lot of puppy energy and playfulness. A suggested home for Maverick is one that is already dog savvy, only with older kids and adults, and has the time to give to a couple of walks (or jogging?) per day. Maverick is a guy who wants your attention for playing and is not a couch potato. In looking at Maverick's picture taken when he first arrived at Pasadena Humane, we see a somewhat shy looking dog with some probable anxious panting. But take a look at those soft, hopeful eyes! He is looking for just the right fur-ever home . . . is yours the one? Learn more about our virtual adoption process .

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Whippet/Hound Mix | 10-months old | 30 pounds | Adoption Fee: $400Just look at that pretty face!!

This young cutie is a very enthusiastic and energetic girl.

She still is a puppy so she does have puppy antics. She gets along good with the other resident dogs, loves to play and

knows the command sit.

On first meeting, she will be shy and cautious, barking a bit but it only takes a few minutes and she calms down.

Lady Bea seems very attentive and intelligent and looks you right in the eye when you are talking to her. She is food motivated so these two combined should make her easily trainable.

We are working on crate training, she must have had a very bad experience before she came to us while crated or just always crated, hard to say, but with patience and love I think she will trust you.

She does well being gated in any area of the home while we are working on the crate.

Lady Bea is housebroken and she will let you know when she wants out either by looking at you and barking or running back and forth to the door so pay attention to her signals!!

Lady Bea has a tendency to pull on the leash when walking, we are working on this and she is learning quickly.

She is a high energy pup and would be best suited in an active family environment. She would be a great hiking, running or all around outdoor companion.

Lady Bea also is a cuddle bug, if she could fit in your lap and sleep that's where she would be.

Lady Bea would make a amazingly fun, loving and sensitive companion to one very lucky family!

Lady Bea does need a big fenced in yard to run and play, or someone that is dedicated to her exercise and energy needs, a doggy park would be awesome!!

Pick Lady Bea!!!

The adoption fee covers the cost of the animal's spay/neuter surgery, microchipping, FIV/FeLK testing (for cats) or Heartworm Testing (for dogs), deworming and all core age appropriate vaccinations. For the most complete information regarding this animal, and all of our adoptable pets, please ensure you are visiting our website directly at www.RescueCrew.org. You can also access the necessary online adoption application here as well. Thank you.

animal.description:
Huey is a big goofy boy in search of a home with a big amount of love to give! Huey is an 11 month old large mixed breed boy in search of a home with the time, energy and patience for a puppy. Although almost a year old, Huey is very much still a puppy and will require all the same things a puppy needs; socialization, positive reinforcement training, patience, time and plenty of exercise. 

Huey is so far a social boy at the shelter and gets excited to be around other dogs and would do great with another social dog in his new home. He loves to play(especially fetch!) and will need a home with the time to take Huey on plenty of walks, adventures or other outings. Huey is a big boy and doesn't realize his size, and although will make a great cuddle buddy after he is worn out from the day, would do best in a home without small children that he can knock over.

If you think Huey is the boy for you, he is sure to steal your heart with his goofy nature and adorable personality.

TRAINING AND SOCIALIZATION:
Puppies require time, patience, and commitment to help them grow into happy, healthy adult dogs. To give the full commitment that puppies need, we do not permit adopters to adopt more than 1 puppy, of the same age or from the same litter. While it may seem cute, and even easier, to adopt 2 puppies at the same time, research shows that it's not a good idea. Littermate Syndrome can occur when 2 puppies are raised together. Their deep bond can impede their ability to properly socialize with humans and other dogs during this critical developmental period which can lead to behavioral issues as adult dogs, including reactivity and aggression. Please also consider force free, science-based training to help your new puppy become a happy, well socialized family member that won't end up back at our shelter. To find a trainer on island, visit fearfreepets.com or apdt.com.

animal.description:
Mrs. Maisel is a recent return.

Before she came back, we were told it would be best if she was put down. Needless to say, it made us nervous to see what Maisel had become. What we took back was not what we feared. What we have is a sweet, kind, loving dog. She’s energetic, and her greetings to new dogs can be a little rough. She doesn’t understand that her exuberant enthusiasm isn’t always the best approach. Sometimes it might even sound like she could be mean. Really she just wants to meet someone sooooo bad. She would do better with a more relaxed dog in the home. Playful is fine, but someone who won’t try to boss her around. And absolutely no cats. She does enjoy a game of chase, so smaller animals wouldn’t do well with her. She needs an experienced owner, someone who knows how to train a dog. But she will repay you in love and gratitude tenfold over what you give her. She’s really just a happy sweet dog. 

Maisel is a 1.5 year old pit mix. She is spayed, up to date on vaccines, and microchipped.

Her adoption fee is $175.

animal.description:
Say hello to Arlo! He's a handsome guy looking for his forever home. He will be a year old later this month (Jan 2021). He weighs in at  60 pounds, which he feels is the perfect lap dog weight. 

Arlo loves toys! But they definitely need to be durable--he will make short work of destroying the wimpy ones. He is good with other dogs his size and currently goes to daycare a couple days a week. He has had no exposure to small dogs and very limited exposure to cats. 

Arlo's other favorite pastime is cuddling with his people. As you can see in his pictures he is a bit of a couch potato and a ham for the camera.

He has to watch his sodium intake but doesn't require a special food, just care in selecting his treats.

Due to his enthusiastic nature, Arlo will be best in a home with no small children. Arlo is up for a road trip and rides well in the car. 

Arlo sleeps in his crate at night but isn't sold on the idea during the day. It's a work in progress. He is also making progress on his leash walking.

For more information about Arlo contact The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387. He's in the Kansas City metro, but transport is available to the right home. 

INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET? Fill out an Adoption Application now! Appointments can also be made to meet a pet by calling us at 913-671-PETS (913-671-7387).  

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
Prior to adoption, our animals are: 
**Tested for diseases 
**Vaccinated 
**Spayed/neutered 
**Microchipped 

NO COST adoptions with an encouraged donation are accepted. 

The Pet Connection also offers adopters a FREE veterinary examination and a medical care support plan for 60 days after adoption, as well as lifetime behavioral training, safe sanctuary for pets returned in emergency situations, extensive assistance with lost and found pets, and other expert pet services in a variety of areas, including pet selection, behavioral issues, general training, nutrition, and transition to adoptive homes.

Please visit our website at www.thepetconnection.org for more information about The Pet Connection and for a full listing of our available pets, 

Call or text The Pet Connection at 913-671-7387 if you can foster, adopt, or sponsor a special needs dog or cat! 

The Pet Connection is a membership organization operating a no-kill adoption center in Shawnee, Kansas.

animal.description:
Hi! Are you looking at me? My name is Petey and I am a very sweet, loving boy. Second Chance thinks I may have been miss-treated because of how scared I am with people. I am a very shy boy looking for a loving person to show me that not all people are bad. I would do best as an only dog with someone who has a yard for me to play in. Unfortunately, I am heart-worm positive awaiting treatment, but don't like that stop you from meeting me because Second Chance will pay for my treatment. Schedule an appointment to meet me today. 

COVID-19 UPDATE: We are operating strictly by appointment ONLY. Please note that staff is limited right now, the best way to get in touch with us is by email: info@secondchancespca.org. Due to the volume of calls, only the most urgent calls will be returned. For information regarding the adoption process please visit our website or read the information below THANK YOU.

ADOPTION PROCESS: If you are interested in adopting from Second Chance
SPCA, please come to our adoption center during business hours. Appointments are required. Adopters will visit with an adoption counselor and complete a short application. Adopters must live within the Dallas-Fort Worth metroplex and be at least 21 years old. Renters must provide proof of pet deposit and/or written permission by landlord to have a pet.

ADOPTION FEES: Includes spay/neuter, age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, fecal, and heartworm test (dogs) or FeLV/FIV test (cats). animal.description:
Leah is  a five month old, bouncy Lab X Pit. We took the puppy in when she found herself on a shelter e-list.

Leah and her siblings were found at 2 months last October abandoned in a box behind a gas station in Phoenix.
	
Leah, like many pups is "mouthy". With her needle-puppy-teeth she was returned by both the foster and the adopter for non-piercing "bites" (ie scratches.) In another month, at 6 months of age, she should have all of her adult teeth in and those teeth will be far easier to deal with!

AHS spayed Leah and made sure she was up to date with her shots. They discovered an umbilical hernia which they also repaired.

Within hours of her arrival, we discovered that Leah knows "sit" and is quickly learning "stay." Leah also knows how to use a doggy door.  She is learning "no" and is already becoming less mouthy. She just wants love and hugs.

Leah also knows how to walk on the leash, although she needs further training so as not to pull when excited.

She loves chewable treats which I am sure helps with her teething.

We set up a nice crate and bed and she loves relaxing in it!

Since most of our dogs are older and therefore mellower than she is, Leah having a hard time being accepted because she just wants to run and play...like any big puppy would...and they are put off by her energy level. 

She would do wonderfully with a person who likes to hike or run....

Leah is a sweet, loving and intelligent puppy of about 35 lbs and is going to be a big dog. You can tell by looking at her big feet!!

Leah will make someone a delightful family member.
We do home checks and reference checks as we want an ideal home for this little girl.

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email US at

michelel@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Miley

Estimated Breed : Labrador Retriever and Shepherd Mix

Approximate Age: 3 years

Approximate Weight: approx. 45 lbs

Currently Living at: Boarding

Adoption Fee: $375

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Miley is a sweet, shy but happy, young girl who is ready and waiting for a loving forever home where she can run, play and be your best buddy. Miley would do best with a fenced yard, as she has lots of energy and likes to hear herself talk. Not ideal for apartments. She adores human interaction!

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Shyla is a sweet medium sized dog probably between 1-2 yrs. We first saw Shyla at Animal Services where she was a surrender. All the other dogs were barking and Shyla was just watching us. Shyla was brought to Florida from Tennessee. The people moved again and just left her and so she was surrendered. She has obviously had puppies recently and has at least a couple mammary tumors that the vet hopes will shrink now that she's been spayed. 
Shyla was so quiet because she is mostly deaf but she can hear barks and whistles. She is a very calm dog that just wants to be with you. She wants to see you or she starts looking for you and she goes potty and wants to come right back inside. She seemed to be ok with cats and horses but would probably be better as an only dog. She gets along with other dogs but they seem to pick on her because she is different. She wants to lay beside you and just be wherever you are. If you are looking for a sweet, quiet mellow Velcro dog Shyla may be your girl.

animal.description:
IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS PET, PLEASE COMPLETE AN ADOPTION APPLICATION FOUND ON OUR WEBSITE HTTP://FUREVERTAILS.COM/ADOPTIONS. We process applications ONLY - there is no guarantee that you will get a response to an inquiry.

MEET AVERY:

Avery and her 2 siblings (Adam and Angel) were dropped off at a high-intake shelter and spent over a month of their young life there. Avery is a Great Dane/Lab mix and is estimated to be approximately 6 months old. Avery is a very shy and will need a patient family willing to work with her to boost her confidence. It is evident that she was deprived of that important social interaction when she was much younger and now is leary of humans. It is very important that applicants understand that she will need time, patience and positive reinforcment. It is going to take time for her to become comfortable and consistency is very important. She would benefit from training as that will encourage her to build a strong bond with her owner. She really enjoys the company of other dogs that will engage in play with him and it would be very beneficial for his furever home to have another medium or large breed social dog. She would likely be best in a home without cats. At this time we feel a home with older children would be best as she spooks easily with loud noises and fast actions. Avery is going to grow to be a big girl, maybe not a full Great Dane XL size but he will still be a large dog. She is not a good fit for an apartment, condo or mobile home lifestyle. She will need a family that has some breed knowledge and someone experienced in working with timid and fearful dogs; she is not a goodfit for a first time dog owner. Avery has a great understanding of house manners and is crate trained! She will need continued work with walking on a leash and help building her trust and confidence as he is just now finally getting to experience the big world and enjoying puppy-life! She will need a home where someone is home more often than not as Danes thrive when they are around their people. Avery is a sweet puppy, and although she is fearful at the moment, she will eventually make some lucky family very happy!

Angel is:
Current on Rabies and Distemper
Dewormed
Heartworm Tested: Negative
Receiving Heartworm and Flea Prevention
Microchipped
Spayed

ADOPTION FEE: $275

FUREVER TAILS IS A NON-PROFIT, NO-KILL, FOSTER HOME BASED ANIMAL RESCUE BASED OUT OF OAKLAND TOWNSHIP, MI. OUR FOSTER ANIMALS ARE LIVING IN FOSTER HOMES AND TREATED LIKE FAMILY UNTIL THEY FIND THEIR OWN FUREVER FAMILIES. OUR ADOPTION PROECESS REQUIRES AN APPLICATION TO BE COMPLETED AND APPROVED BEFORE A MEET-N-GREET WITH THE ANIMAL CAN TAKE PLACE. ADOPTION FEES ARE NECESSARY TO HELP US COVER VETTING COSTS FOR OUR RESCUED ANIMALS. UNFORTUNATELY AT THIS TIME WE ARE NOT CURRENTLY ADOPTING OUT OF THE STATE OF MI.

animal.description:
Ramble is funny, lovable, smart boy. He is a 1 year/19lb/Terrier Mix. He's big enough to be durable, and he's still small enough to fit just about anywhere.

This dog is a sweetheart who absolutely loves affection. Ramble fell in love with my 10 year old daughter almost immediately. The feeling was mutual. My daughter says he's her favorite foster so far (and I've had 9 others during the past year). Ramble has been wonderful with her.

He can actually be quite the ham when he wants attention, and he's got a flair for the dramatic (in the best possible way). He loves playing with his toys and will toss them in the air and fling them across the room on his own. He's a huge clown.

Because Ramble is a young, playful dog, he will sometimes grab something he shouldn't have - like a discarded paper towel, or a ziplock bag, sock, etc. - and proceed to play "keep away" while the humans try to take it from him. And he's totally laughing at the humans the entire time they're chasing him. But he hasn't tried to destroy any of the things he's put in his mouth.

Ramble is good in his crate, and he's been good about going outside to potty. If not taken out fairly quickly after being let out of his crate in the morning, he will lift his leg in the house, but he hasn't actually peed on anything yet. So far, a verbal correction has been enough to prevent any accidents.

He has been fully vetted. He tested very light positive for heartworms, so we opted for the slow-kill method. He was given a ProHeart injection and will be heartworm negative by the time he needs his next ProHeart.

Hail Mary Rescue, a 501c3 non profit, saves dogs from southeast Louisiana shelters. It is a foster-based rescue which gives pets the opportunity to live in home settings where they are house and crate trained, learn basic obedience commands, and are well socialized, many with children and other dogs. Exposure to cats depends on the foster's home. Adoption fee is $200 for LA adoptions; $400 (includes transportation fee for out-of-state adoptions). All dogs are completely vetted, vaccinated, spay/neutered, and micro-chipped prior to adoption. See your new best friend? Submit an application today https://form.jotform.com/92111104800135 A volunteer will contact you usually within 24 hrs.

Located in Sidney NE
1-3 years old
Labrador Retriever mix
Good with other dogs
Cats unknown
Good with the kids he has met at the shelter
Doing well on house training 
Knows some commands or working on crate training and he does great but he wants to be with his people when possible

Did you miss out on dating that frat boy in college? Do you miss your "bro's" in your new life as an adult? Look no further because Greggor is the answer! This dude is literally a frat boy in a dog and he needs YOU! 

Greggor arrived this month after finding himself at an overfull shelter over the holidays. He is a sweet goober of a dog who, for reasons we cannot understand, kept being overlooked. He is happy-go-lucky despite being confused after weeks of sitting in the shelter environment. He is a huge boy who has no idea his large size and just wants to play and cuddle. He will make an amazing companion for camping, hiking, fishing and other outdoor activities and adventures where his XL size and oafish nature won't get in the way, aka this isn't your stealthy hunting champion. Despite being the complete package Greggor still needs your help! He needs a foster or adoptive home immediately. If interested in helping this deserving lug please contact us!! 

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our VOICEMAIL at (402)957-1578

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Please read this description carefully before submitting an application for Sonny. There are specific requirements that his new owners need to have in order for him to be successul.

Sonny came to us from North Carolina where he was found as a stray in November and he was terrified of people. You could see that he was curious and wanted to trust but it was obvious that he had never been handled by a person in his first 8 months of life. He is just under a year oldl and has made incredible progress in his foster home assisted by his two confident dog mentors and awesome people, but he will most likely always be cautious and very timid around anyone new. Once he learns to trust you, he is the sweetest, most playful, exhuberant pup around! He LOVES other dogs and we feel that he will do best with a confident, playful, tolerant dog of similar size who can be his new mentor. He follows the lead of other dogs and is learning how to navigate the world with their guidance. We will be prioritizing homes with another dog in place so this can continue. Sonny also needs people who understand dog behavior and can coach new people he meets on how to approach him properly and earn his trust. He needs a confident, kind leader and his new new people need to have experience with timid dogs or to be willing to learn. He is still young and is SO curious, you can see that Sonny wants to grow and trust, he just needs someone who will continue to work with him and expose him to the world so he can move past his fears. We would also strongly recommend working with a trainer who can guide this process so Sonny can find success. He doesn't have a mean bone in his body and there have been no signs of any negative behavior towards people or other dogs. He has never met a cat so that is completely unknown. Even though he is perfectly safe, we don't feel he would do well with young children due to their energy and unpredictability. Sonny is easily scared and needs a quieter home where he can learn to trust. He is very active and athletic but he gets fearful of new people out on walks and defaults to returning home. Until he can move beyond that, a securely fenced yard would be best to allow him to get his energy out. He LOVES playing with toys and interacting with his humans. He is fully housebroken and he is BEYOND adorable. He is a perfect medium size, around 50 pounds, and has very good manners in the home. He is crate trained and is gaining confidence by the day. Please contact us if you feel you are a good fit for Sonny. We plan to take the process of acclimating him to his new home slowly and will most likely need to do several meet and greets at his house and yours so out of state applications will not be considered. Sonny is being fostered in Chesire, CT. Send any questions to info@spottydogrescue.org

animal.description: Looking for a hiking or running partner? How about a fun, energetic girl? Look no further! I am Jujubee, an adult Pit Bull mix. I was found as a stray in the city of Harrisburg. I think with proper socialization I will be a better fit for another dog friend, but for now I would do best as your one and only! Trust me, I am plenty!

I was surrendered to the shelter because I had been used as a breeder dog but wasn't needed any longer so they chose to have me find a home instead. I am a shy dog and in need of socialization. A fenced in yard would be ideal as I cannot be trusted loose outside. I'll need a patient home while I learn what it's like to be a house dog with a family of my own. Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $60.00. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. We are committed to helping the animals that enter our doors and finding each the best possible forever home. CCHS has been inspected and licensed by the Department of Animal Health - DATCP. Our license is #268235-DS

animal.special_needs_notes: Tucker needs to be the only animal in the home and the adopter needs to sign a contract and follow through on taking him to a training program that we are willing to assist with financially. Due to the fact that he was not properly socialized at an early age. He is now afraid of other dogs, and he chases cats. He can walk on a leash near other dogs, sometimes even touch noses, but off leash he does not understand that he needs to stay out of other dogs faces and has been attacked. Only experienced dog owners and we will thoroughly background check to keep Tucker safe. He also pulls on a leash and will jump on people, so needs to go to a home with no kids AND NO DOG PARKS.

animal.description:
SONNY - Courtesy posting

Meet Sonny, a sweet 15 year old chi-blend that weighs in at 9 lbs. Sonny’s mom got really sick and passed away after being in hospice care for a while. Some kind neighbors took this little man in and are determined to find a home to love him in his twilight years. 

Sonny is pretty healthy with no recurring issues. He has a healthy appetite and gets around well as long as he doesn’t have to use stairs (they scare him). 

He is not house broken and has outright refused to use puppy pads, but with a home that has easy access to the backyard with no stairs (or the ability to carry him up and down them) he could hopefully learn!

Sonny is a lap dog and loves chilling on the couch with his person. He gets along ok with dogs and kids, and he doesn’t make much noise. He does seem to have some issues with his teeth and would benefit from a good cleaning. 

He is UTD on shots, on HW preventative, and neutered.

His adoption donation is $100.00.

If you are interested in the above dog, please do not email us and tell us that you are interested, but submit an adoption application. The link for the application is below.

To submit an application go here……chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/

An application must be submitted and approved before a meet-n-greet can be scheduled.

Your current dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered unless a veterinarian has determined that your current pet(s) should not be fixed due to medical reasons. They must also be up-to-date on shots and on HW preventative.

Reference checks and a home visit are required so SE dogs can only be adopted in NC/SC, TN, AL, VA, MD and GA.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Jonah and I am at the Santa Maria Campus. I am a 6-year-old, male, Siberian Husky who is eager for a new home!

The first thing you'll probably notice about me are my eyes. Boy are they a crystal-clear blue!! All the better to adore you with! It's easy to feel a strong connection with me quick, because I love eye contact and sharing that bond (and it's pretty hard to look away from me--the ability to mesmerize is my superpower!). 

I'm a lot of fun to be around too. I'm very active, love to run, and would love to have someone to jog with. I also like to relax, and just cuddle up with you. I bond deeply to my people. I do want a home with adults and older teens--kids and younger teens might not be able to read some of my body language as well!

So if you're looking for an adventure, I'm your boy. I'll go on every hike, beach trip, and road trip with you that you like! 

Ready to adopt or want to hear more about me? The shelter is open by appointment seven days a week! Just email adopt@sbhumanesociety.org to make an appointment today!

When you take your new pet home, he or she will have been spayed/neutered, up to date on vaccinations, provided with a permanent microchip identification and a certificate for a free veterinary exam. Our partners at Purina brand dog and cat food also provide food to get you home.

animal.description: Zoltan is a sweet boy who came to the shelter with some wounds that needed attention from the PACC clinic. We wish he could tell us exactly what happened, but he's not talking. We do know that he was at PACC all the way back in 2016, so he's not too thrilled to be back here again. Despite his condition, Zoltan has been very friendly and affectionate to the people he's met at the shelter, and has been easy to walk. He spent some time in a temporary home and we learned that he's housetrained and loves to sleep on the couch or with his person. While Zoltan is a lover of people, he's a little choosier when it comes to other dogs, so we recommend a meet-and-greet with any resident pups. Zoltan is a sweet boy who would love to get out of the shelter and into a home. If he sounds like your type of guy, he's ready to head home with you today!

***Please Read Entire Post**

The first step is to complete an adoption application via our website, www.cofas.org (click on Adoption Information, Available Dogs, Dog Adoption Application). 
All of our adoptable animals are in foster homes. A meeting can be arranged for approved applicants. 
 
Once we have reviewed your application we will get back to you as soon as possible. 
We have the right to decline an application if it is not a good fit for that particular animal. 
 
__________________

This handsome boy is Simba.  He is an 18 month old Great Pyrenees.  He is a pet and NOT a working Great Pyrenees.  He prefers the couch and will chase all types of farm animals.   :)
He was turned into a rural kill shelter because he was not a good fit for apartment life.  He is about 85lbs but is a bit thin and needs to gain some weight.
He walks great on a leash and knows how to sit.
He is a big boy and does get excited when playing and may be too much for small children under 10 years of age.

We are looking for a new home for Simba that has Great Pyrenees experience and/or knowledgeable about the quirky breed and has a secure fenced in yard.  No exceptions....please!
Due to the virus and state restrictions we are not doing out of state adoptions for Simba.  Also, a home visit is required for adoption for this boy.

 


Any questions about Simba, please contact his foster Mom at kittypuppylv@aol.com

_________________________


Not yet ready to adopt? You can sponsor a pet now to help pay for medical expenses, special diets, toys and treats, emergency medical care, etc., to provide for him or her during foster care. Our adoption fee rarely covers our expenses, so any size donation is appreciated! Click the Sponsor Me! logo to make a donation. You can also donate by check or Paypal by visiting our website at www.cofas.org 


 All of our dogs are fostered in our homes so we know their temperaments. They are spayed or neutered, up to date on shots, de-wormed, heartworm tested (and treated if necessary), and on flea and heartworm prevention. Our adoption fee begins at $195.00 for all of our dogs and puppies. Our goal is to match our animals to the best home possible. Please email info@cofas.org for more information. You can also fill out an application at www.cofas.org

animal.description:
A word from Lillith herself:

Hi! 
My name is Lilith, but my foster family calls me  Lilly or Lilly Beans. They have all kinds of funny nicknames for the doggos here, so I’ll take it as a compliment. I am a one year old Husky/German Shepherd mix girl searching for this thing that my foster mom calls a forever family. You see, I thought I had one and had a great time chasing the chickens at my first home and that made my mom and dad really upset because I killed some of them. I didn’t mean to hurt them, but something just takes over me and I chase fast moving things. My foster mom tells me that’s why I can’t play with the kitties in my foster home. I haven’t hurt the kitties but I’m super excited to see them and chase them and that makes my foster mom nervous given my chicken killing past. She says that my forever home can’t have any kitties just to keep everyone safe. And that’s ok by me as long as I have some nice people, kids and even friendly doggos to play with me. I love my doggy foster brothers and sisters and my foster mom says I am all crazy husky in my play and I play rough like a big dog. I’m very noisy in my play and that can be scary for some people, but I really get into my play. I do tend to get bossy, so my new doggy brother or sister will have to be ok with that. It can be a bit much for some doggies I am told. You see, my foster family has a female husky too and my foster mom tells me that she’s the alpha. I don’t know what that means but I always try to push her buttons to see if I can be in charge. So I guess I’m just trying to see if I can be as cool and in charge as she is. Who would think that a GIRL husky could be in charge of two big boy huskies? Cool right? I want to be just like her! So I got a little off track. I was talking about kids too, not just doggo siblings. My foster family has two big kids that my foster mom says are teenagers and I think they are pretty swell because they are big enough to bounce and play with me and I don’t have to worry about knocking them over when I get the zoomies. My foster mom thinks I may be best with bigger kids or at least sturdy enough for me to really play, because man o man do I love to play! AND my kids even let me sleep in their bed! That’s the best, I love sleeping with the people, and they tell me I’m a good girl and I don’t hog the bed. I really like to spend as much time as I can with my family and I get nervous when my people leave. It’s pretty awesome that my foster mom is working from home right now because of covid so I don’t have to be home alone all day, and I may like a family like that for my forever family. I will go in a kennel when my family has to go out for something, but it’s not really my favorite. They say it’s to make sure I stay safe because I get nervous when they leave. It’s not so bad I guess. Oh, that brings me to my other thing that my foster mom calls my quirk. So I have figured out I can jump a 4’ fence to go find my family if they’re in the front yard and I’m in the back or sometimes just for fun to go play with the neighbor’s dog. My mom says I’ll need at least a 6’ fence to keep me from trying to play catch me if you can. I think it’s a fun game, but my foster dad didn’t think it was very fun when he was home sick and I did it. OOPS ???? total doggy face palm moment. 
All in all my foster mommy says I’m a really sweet, lovable and sassy girl, I just need to find a great family who will love me and help me grow into the great doggo I should be. My foster dad says I have just enough Shepherd in me to be super smart and trainable overriding my crazy carefree huskiness and I have a natural instinct to want to protect my family. Did I mention I LOVE my people? They are seriously the best! But my foster mom says I have to find a great forever family of my own so she can help save other dogs just like me. 
If you think I sound like a great girl for you, please fill out the adoption application and send it to Cindy and Paula that run the rescue. They say I am spayed, up to date on my vaccinations, heart worm prevention, flea and tick prevention, microchipped and ready to go home. I just need my family to find me.  Could it be you?

Age:  6 yrs.
Weight:  16 lbs.
Good with dogs:  dog selective
Good with cats:  unsure
Good with kids:  12 yrs. +
Energy level:  low
Good with men/strangers:  yes
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  none

Additional info:

Karloff is doing well in his foster home.   We are still getting to know him but so far he has been a very friendly boy that loves hanging out with his person and  does not like to be fussed over too much. He is pretty mellow and likes to be taken out for regular walks. He does have some minor leash aggression and is dog selective as he was attacked by a dog in the past.   He seems to prefer calm dogs that are closer to his size, but ultimately may prefer being the only dog in the home. He may be able to live with another dog if it's the right fit.   This may take some patience and time on the human's part and willingness to work with the dogs to help them bond. 

He is housetrained and he will be fine in a home with children that are older (12 yrs.+) that can understand to give him space. Karloff is not crate trained and will bark pretty loudly.   We aren't sure about separation anxiety as his foster has not yet left him alone. He is also low shedding, but not hypoallergenic. Overall, he is an easy going dog that just needs the right person to work with his fears of other dogs.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

Meet Sammy! He is a 2.5 year old Boston Terrier mix that weighs 30 lbs.   He is definitely one of a kind meaning he is a bit opinionated. He needs to be adopted by family with either no children or grown children that has a household with consistency on a daily basis. I honestly feel that Sammy is going to make a wonderful pet but we have to find the right home for him and his potential adopters.  We know there is a family out there for this stellar stud muffin, we just have to find the right fit.  If you think you might be the one to adopt him, please email us at Longj1003@aol.com and katybug6067@gmail.com. Thanks for opting to adopt.

animal.description:
Beautiful Tigger is about 70 pounds and is approx a year old.  He recently had an altercation with a very angry porcupine and ended up with over 100 quills in his face, neck, mouth and head area.  After a very long surgery to remove them all, he unfortunately lost an eye.  He was already very underweight so it took him awhile to recover.  At first he was so weak, he could not even go for a walk!  Now that he has put on weight and recovered from his ordeal, he acts as though nothing ever happened and is full of puppy love and energy! Tigger absolutely loves everyone he meets and will try to give hugs and kisses; he even loves the vet! He is very food-motivated and very smart so he thrives on training time.  He only knows a few commands but with a dedicated person to help guide him, he will become a model doggy citizen in no time!
According to his DNA results, Tigger is Lab, Rotti, Chow and ‘other.’  In the other, we believe he has some type of herding breed because he will chase trucks if he has a chance.  We think there may also be some Kangaroo because this boy can jump!  He doesn’t jump on people but jumps straight into the air likes he’s on a pogo stick.  He would be a great candidate for agility training.  Tigger does have a high prey drive so NO cats or small animals in the home.  He MUST have a 6ft or higher, securely fenced yard.  Because of his high energy, kids must be over 10yrs old, and he must have an active family that will take him on plenty of jogs and hiking trips.  Play dates with other large dogs are a must... or even another young, playful dog in the home would be ideal.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi everyone, name is Billy! I was living in a Colorado shelter for the past few months. The nice shelter staff loved me so much, they put out a plea to find me a foster home or rescue. Now I am in the care of Rejection Collection Boxer Rescue and settling into my foster home.

I am a happy go lucky, loving boy. When I get excited I tend to get a bit mouthy and/or licky. I don't bite down or anything, I just get so excited I don't know how to contain myself.

I am potty trained, do fine in a crate, and enjoy exploring the fenced in yard. I am still learning the ropes in my foster home. My foster mom says I am doing really well, I just need to brush up on a few manners. I am a smart boy and seem to learn quickly if you take the time to teach me.

I am getting to know my little foster fur sister, Micka. I like her so much I want to play rough and box her in the face. I like licking her face and sometimes try to start mouth wrestling. My foster mom usually stops me because I am bigger and a bit too much for Micka. Maybe once she gets used to me she'll try to wrestle back.

There are two kitties in my foster home. So far I am VERY curious, to the point that I am obsessed. I have tried to chase one of the kitties and would like to taste him. I don't understand why that's so bad? Based on my intense behavior so far, my foster mom says that I would probably do best in a home without cats or small critters.The shelter said I do well with female dogs, but prefer to be the only male. My initial age estimate was about 8 years, but the RCBR vet thinks I might be closer to 6 years old. My foster mom says I do seem to have the energy of a younger dog. I say age is just a number anyway.

Stay tuned for more updates as my foster family gets to know me.

Love,
Billy

animal.description:
If you live an active lifestyle, Kate is ready to be your best friend and loyal companion! Already having a great recall off-leash, she has huge potential to be the perfect dog for an outdoor enthusiast who can give her the exercise she needs daily to be at her best. If you love all of the traits of a border collie...smart, spunky, energetic, attaches quickly to family, and a big cuddler....then Kate is your girl! 

Kate is shy and hesitant upon first meeting new people and new dogs, but she opens up with time and then just wants to hang by your side. She needs time and space so she can check out new things on her own schedule. She is skeptical and afraid around new noises and movement, like walking near a busy road, so patience and training exercises would really help her gain some confidence. We have no doubt she will get there with time, as she has already made huge improvements since arriving in her foster home two weeks ago. She plays well with the resident dog (a large male hound) but she is more interested in what her humans are doing. She does like to steal toys from doggy friends, so she would be best suited to a dog who doesn't mind sharing. She is happy to nap at our feet while we are on work calls, but she is not the type of dog who will nap all day. She would do best in a home where her family is with her for a good part of the day as she can get anxious when she is alone. 

She has some adorable mannerisms, like bouncing with excitement after a ball and turning her head dramatically to listen to new noises. Her curiosity has gotten her into some interesting situations and has had us laughing hysterically with her antics. She would do well if she was given a "job" and wasn't left to her own devices, at least for the first few months until she settles in. When she's tired, she is a true cuddle bug and is an A+ snuggler. She will sleep in her crate with the door open, but we haven't graduated to closing the crate door yet. She rarely barks and hasn't tried to hop over our 3.5 foot outdoor fenced space. She is currently attending a level 1 life skills class and is a quick study, very eager to please her humans. She would be an absolute rockstar at herding trials, agility, flyball or another dog sport. In a former home she did great with kids. I expect she would be shy at first and then friendly especially if they have a ball to throw for her to chase! She hasn't been tested around cats.

Kate is going to be a fabulous dog for someone who loves to hike, run, bike, ski, or otherwise spend time outside and have her tag along! Although she needs some training in the short-term, we have no doubt she will learn quickly and will be an extremely rewarding dog. Border Collie mix, 1 year old, 35 lbs, apply here:
http://longtraildogs.org/adoption-application/

****If you are interested in meeting Draco or learning more about the adoption process, please submit an online adoption application at careforanimals.org. Thank you!****

Draco is a young yellow Lab mix that is full of energy and joy. He was passed over at the shelter for almost two months, we're not really sure why. While he is young and a little stubborn he is as sweet as they come. He is most happy playing with his dog friends. He loves to be part of a big play group where he romp and play. He needs a little work on manners and we're hoping Paws in Prison will be the spot for that. 


Draco is fully vaccinated, microchipped, and neutered. His adoption fee is $250.

Draco is in the Paws in Prison program where he receives obedience training. He will graduate from Paws in Prison on 3/20/2021.  The dogs in this program are trained under the AKC Canine Good Citizen standards and are specifically selected to be family and companion dogs. They spend 24 hours a day with their trainers. For that reason, they will do best in homes where they are primarily inside dogs and spend lots of time with their families. The adoptive family will receive his training journal. This journal documents his arrival from the shelter, daily training progress, and interactions with the trainers.

CARE's adoptable pets are specifically evaluated and selected to be family and companion animals. We place them in foster homes where they live in the home environment and become part of the family while awaiting permanent adoption. For that reason, they will do best in homes where they are primarily inside pets and spend lots of time with their families.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Clay County Animal Rescue & Shelter is located at 14400 Hwy. 45 in Louisville, IL. Our phone number is 618-665-3005. The shelter is open to the public 1-3 Monday-Saturday. Sundays we are open 1-4 to the public. If those times don't work, please call to set up a time to visit.

The typical adoption fee for dogs is $150. It includes vaccination, deworming , spay/neuter, heartworm testing on dogs of age and microchipping, which is now mandatory by state law. Some dogs we discount to as little as $50 due to sponsorship. Some dogs we ask a higher adoption fee, which helps us recoup expenses on heartworm treatment on other dogs.

All cats are spayed/neutered/vaccinated/flea treated/dewormed and microchipped prior to adoption. Cat adoption fees range from $60-$100. We spay/neuter/microchip/vaccinate and deworm all kittens and cats, prior to adoption. Our shyer/less adoptable cats are classed as "barn cats" and are free with a completed/approved barn cat application, which can be found on our website.

For updates on adoption events and more pics of pets available, go to our website, www.claycountyshelter.com or look for us on Facebook.

animal.description:
Meet Binx.

Nickname: Binxy 
Age: 5 yrs
Breed: Terrier mix
Weight: 25 lbs
Foster home: Madison, WI
Home state: Illinois 
Activity level: Medium
Sleep style: Buried under blankets in bed w/humans 
Snore-o-meter: 0
Bark-o-meter: 0
Fashion: Fleece pullover
Favorite season: Winter
Commands: Come, sit, wait, off, down & diaper (this is his cue to come and let you put his diaper on)
Walk out song: Party Up ~DMX
Personality: Gentle, outdoorsy, codependent, kind, alert, sensitive, loyal & adventurous
Best feature: Yoda ears
Friendly with all: kids, cats, dogs
Loves: Hiking in the snow, long winter’s naps, artisan cheese, scrambled eggs, car rides, ear rubs, Zoomies in the yard, snuggle time & Netflix
Bucket List: Road trip to Colorado to hike in the mountains and running on the shores of Lake Michigan

*Binx was struck by a car in February 2020. Although he is able-bodied, the accident left him with internal injuries that rendered him incontinent. This means Binx ALWAYS WEARS A DIAPER unless he’s outside. This is no big deal and doesn’t slow him down at all. 

*Binx is looking for an active family who will include him in all of their adventures (road trips, brewery outings, camping, hanging out with the neighbors). He’s a busy body outdoors and then a super snuggler indoors. He craves physical touch and wants to be your constant companion. He would love other canine companions but would be just as happy if he was your one and only. If you have children to give him extra lovies, that would be even better!

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bentley is a 6 year old rat terrier mix! He was abandoned by his owners and set for euthanasia. Bentley is the cutest and the most Sweetest boy in the whole world! He is sight impaired due to a congenital defect but that doesn't stop him one bit! We believe Bentley can see shadows as he doesn't run into anything and he knows exactly where you are at all times but the object has to be very close for him to even see that! Unfortunately he was also found to be heart-worm positive but he is such a nice dog people rallied for him and therefore rescue was able to step in! A dog like Bentley is not one we can resist so we were very excited to save him and we have NOT been disappointed!

Bentley is the type of dog that just makes you fall in love with him! He captured the hearts of so many people in Texas. He then went to a medical foster in Tennessee so he could be treated for heart worm where everyone just fell head over heels in love with him again (Including the vet staff who treated him)! He has been a foster favorite everywhere he has went. After all his traveling We are hoping he can can finally find a place to call Home.

Bentley is fostered with other dogs and is fine with everyone he meets. He doesn't have a mean bone in his little body. He obviously can't really play but he can follow the pack and join in the group for treat time. He is able to do a few stairs on his own and is so smart he even learned how to come in the doggy door when he is done! Bentley loves to be talked to and will talk back - especially if you tell him he's handsome! The higher pitched your voice goes the more he talks and that tail just goes a mile a minute!

Bentley has been around a 9 year old child and really loved her but we would prefer he goes to a quieter home as we think young active kids full time would just be a lot for him. Bentley takes treats nicely, he loves cheese, he LOVES car rides and sits so nicely (shotgun of course)! He is perfectly crate trained- every now and then he will bark but if you tell him no he settles nicely. We are working on housebreaking. He is newly neutered and he did mark when he first came. He is improving now that he understands the routine and knows there the door is. We would suggest a belly band until he settles into his new home and routine with you!

This little dog has been through so much and has met so many new people who have helped him along the way. He has embraced every change in his life and there have been so many! He truly loves everyone and is so grateful for anything you do for him, every sweet word you say to him and every kind pet he gets! He loves couch time and he is one of the most deserving dogs of a forever family! Please don't let his impairment get in the way of adopting him. Bentley is treated like every other dog in his foster home and does perfectly fine. If you think your family and home are a match for this sweet boy please apply!

Bentley is neutered, up to date with vaccines, microchipped, flea/worm treated and treated for heartworm disease. He will need to stay on monthly heartworm prevention for the rest of his life. His adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
Meet Oren! Oren was brought to the shelter as a stray and is now looking for his forever home! This dog loves to hang out outside and just enjoy nature. He'll walk around sniffing for as long as you let him- that is until he decides it's time for zoomies! He's still figuring out how to play with toys though. He'll run after a toy when you throw it unless he gets distracted by more things to sniff. Oren may be a Hound mix, but his soul is that of a Husky! If you know about Huskies, you know that they love to sing for you. Oren is no different! He loves to sing and talk to you, so he's probably not the best fit for an apartment life. If you have another dog, Oren would love to meet them! He got along well with the dogs that he's met here at the shelter. He also met a cat and mostly just wanted to sniff him. Oren is about 3 years old and weighs 40 pounds. 

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please contact Chesterfield County Animal Services at (804) 748-1683, option "0", to schedule an appointment. Office staff are available by phone Monday-Friday 8:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. and Saturday 7:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. The shelter is located at 9300 Public Works Road, Chesterfield, VA 23832.

animal.description:
Jim is an adult Pyr boy who’s looking for a new start on life. Jim was rescued as a stray and needed to be shaved due to severe matting. His rough start hasn’t stopped him from being a very sweet boy though who wants to be inside with his humans most of the time. Jim is doing great with his house manners. He’s not a counter surfer though he can be found curiously running his nose along tabletops and couches looking for goodies left behind :) Needless to say, Jim is very food motivated, which should make continued training a bit easier. Like the rest of us, Jim isn’t having too many visitors these days, but he’s learning not to jump up when greeting new human friends. He could also use some work on his leash skills. Though Jim prefers to be inside, he loves to play with his canine pals and would enjoy a dog sibling to show him the ropes in his new home. Jimmy is quite serious, in an endearing kind of way, but he loves to be hugged and petted! He’s very patient and obedient when his humans need him to be still and he’s very good in the car. Jimmy is an easy-going guy who is a delight to have around. He will make a wonderful addition to a committed and loving family!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
This cutie is Ramon! Ramon came to the shelter as a stray with most of his fur missing due to severe flea dermatitis. You'd never know it now though except for a small square of bare skin along his back! Now that he's healthy, Ramon would love to find his forever home! Ramon probably doesn’t have much experience with being a house pet. He's not really interested in toys or treats (unless we just haven't found his favorites yet!) and mostly just enjoys walking around the yard outside. Ramon has met other dogs here at the shelter and seems to get along well with them, but we'd recommend you bring your dog for a meet and greet to make sure. However, he does not like cats at all! Ramon also does not like being crated. He much prefers to have his freedom! Ramon is hoping to find a patient home who can teach him what it means to truly be a family member! He is a 7 year old Pitbull mix and weighs 60 pounds. 

If you are interested in meeting this pet, please contact Chesterfield County Animal Services at (804) 748-1683, option "0", to schedule an appointment. Office staff are available by phone Monday-Friday 8:30 a.m. to 5:00 p.m. and Saturday 7:30 a.m. to 4:00 p.m. The shelter is located at 9300 Public Works Road, Chesterfield, VA 23832.
animal.name: Ramon

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Got Treats?!?! Donut loves them. A two time offender of our local shelter, once heartworm positive (and treated) came back as a stray with a broken front leg. She has spent many months of rehab to heal and she is now ready to transition to her forever home.

Donut is not fond of passing cars (we probably know why) and take a moment to warm up to people. She is a sweet girl that would make a great companion in your home. The outside world is a bit overwhelming for her so she would not do great in big social settings. She would like a fenced yard and some room to just be a dog.

Donut is about 4 years old and medium size. She does well with other dogs (with proper intros) and is a vocal player. She loves to play tug of war. No Dog Parks for Donut. She is crate trained, house broken and very food motivated. No kids for her - too much excitement.

She just needs an understanding family that will give her the love she deserves and the time to settle in. (we prefer you own your own home as well)

Available in Tampa, FL and surrounding counties ~ Adoption donation $250.00
animal.name: Donut

animal.description:
Guinness is the perfect dog! A perfect day for Guinness includes nice walks in the morning and evening, playtime (he loves to play tug of war very enthusiastically!) and cuddling on the couch with you while watching Netflix. He is house trained and only rarely pulls on his leash when he sees other dogs. Guinness is very patient and sweet with humans! He is crate trained as well. Guinness is a handsome boy who is sure to win your heart! 

Guinness' adoption is $150.00 and includes his neuter, microchip, 30-days pet health insurance, vaccinations, worming and a vet visit voucher.  Some of our dogs have also had heartworm tests, flea treatments, canine influenza vaccines, etc., but it is not standard procedure - please inquire about the specific animal you are interested in.  

We do adopt out-of-state, but require adopters to meet the pet prior to taking it home. The adopters also must have a plan for getting their new addition home before we process an application.  Please check out the airlines, PilotsNPaws, Operation Roger and CARE Transport in Denver for some transport options.

We are open Monday - Friday 11:00 am to 5 pm. You can also call us at 719-680-2385. To fill out the adoption application online please visit our website at noahsarktrinidad.org where you can then email the application with your inquiry. 

Thank you for considering adoption through our shelter.

animal.description:
Meet Benji!

Benji enjoys lying on your lap on the couch and pushing his face into your hand so you will pet him. He's a sweet and gentle older dog who wants to spend his days napping by your side. He's also very smart- he knows "in" and "out", which door to use to go in/out, and will go nudge the door with his nose if he needs to go out and you didn't notice. He knows "sit", and the always popular "treat" and "food".

He is learning not to jump up when he meets new friends, he just gets so excited to meet new people!

He would be most comfortable in a forever home with low activity and lots of love. All he wants is to chill out on your porch with you and bask in the sunlight.

and complete the adoption application.

This process can take up to 7 days.
WE DO WEEKLY APPOINTMENTS FOR ADOPTIONS AFTER APPLICATION APPROVAL!

***CALL 262-968-3858 FOR INFORMATION***

EVERY DOG IS UP TO DATE ON VACCINES FOR THEIR AGE. RABIES VACCINE IF OLD ENOUGH.
SPAYED OR NEUTERED (regardless of age) NO EXCEPTIONS
HEARTWORM and FLEA/TICK PREVENTATIVE
MICROCHIPPED
CERTIFIED VETERINARIAN INSPECTION CERTIFICATE
***WE ARE NOT OPEN TO THE PUBLIC*** ADOPTIONS ARE BY APPOINTMENT ONLY!
Bob is a Lab and Hound mix. He is about 17 Weeks old as of today. (1/13/2021). Bob and his siblings were recused from a kill shelter.
Bob is a fun loving pup. He is doing great on his house training and is very dog social. He loves to play with toys and is a very busy guy. He would love another dog in the house to play with or a very active family.
He currently weighs about 25 pounds.
As always, we never guarantee the breed OR the size they'll be as an adult.
MY ADOPTION FEE is $450.00
We thank you for ADOPTING A HOOVERS HAUSE RESCUE DOG..... every dog adopted allows us to open our homes to save another!

He loves other dogs but he chases my cat and I have taught him no cat, but I would not want him in a home with cats as he would constantly chase them.  He loves kids and people but does take a moment to work up to some men occasionally (twice since i had him here).  Would be a great dog for anyone looking for a constant companion .  He loves to go for walks but needs some training on the leash.  He is so sweet and if you are on couch he will just lay his head on you and chil.  He has to be with someone or another animal constantly. He will go lay his head on the other dogs in the house or sit so close he is touching them.  He came from kill shelter and I rescued him being told he was a Rottie, I am not so sure what he is but pure love. 
text me to meet him: 678-860-9983. I will require application vet reference and home visit!

animal.description:
Lady arrived at NCCR on 1/16/21, pulled from another shelter that ran out of room for her. She is an approximately 10-12 month old spayed female, thought to be a Shepherd/Retreiver mix. Lady is quite friendly and loves people. She seems to get along fine with most other dogs, too. She survived an infection of parvovirus prior to coming to NCCR, and seems to be recovering very well. As with all young dogs, Lady will require ongoing daily training, exercise, lots of play time, and plenty of patience and love to help her become the best dog she can be!

Lady is spayed, vaccinated (including bordetella) and microchipped. Her adoption fee is $215.00. (cash or check only, we are unable to accept credit cards)

Lady is sponsored by Leanne DiNicola,  Julie Rabbit, Karen Larkin, Sandra Pavlock, Keith and Heidi Fowler, Joe and Kate Greulich in honor of Sam and Sarge, Kayme Crowell, David Grayson, Anne Odell, Bob and Trudy Sensel, Melford Swanson and Meg Thering in memory of Jen Leone's dog Chloe.

If you think you might be interested in adopting, your first step should be to complete an adoption application. APPLICATION to ADOPT: Copy and paste this link in your browser to view and complete the application https://forms.gle/NghtT4WTNiaZu7Cg9. You can also select the link, right click and choose open in a new window.

We do adopt out of state, however we do not transport or ship dogs.  Potential adopter must be able and willing to travel to the Rescue to meet the dog they are interested in.  

*PLEASE double check all of the phone numbers that you provide as if they are incorrect, we will be unable to process your application.  Please also let your references know that someone from NCCR will be calling them. Most adoption team members call from their personal phone so advise your references that there may be an unknown number or a private number calling them.  

NYS Registration #RR028.

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 12/23/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Robyn was found as a stray
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Robyn was spayed on 1/7/21. She is up to date on all vaccines and heartworm negative. Robyn is ready for her forever home!
Weight: 36 lbs
Height: 18 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Robyn is young, active, and learning to be a pet. She needs a patient, active family that will continue to work with her. Robyn needs basic training and continued work on crate training. Robyn is good with other dogs and will benefit from another active, well-mannered dog in the home to learn from. She will not be placed in a home with cats. No children under 10 for this girl; Robyn simply plays too rough.

What is my personality like? Robyn came to us via the family of a team member. She didn't get along with the other dog in her home, and one of them had to go. While we are sad it was Robyn, we are happy to be a part of this girl's journey. Since joining our rescue family in December of 2020, Robyn has been learning the basics. She is working on crate training, leash training, and general basic commands. She has a lot of personality and is eager to learn and please.

Robyn is a young dog with a big heart. She is not yet clean in her crate, but is really trying. Crates have clearly not been part of her life in the past and we know it takes time. Robyn loves people and gets very excited to see them. She will mouth and chew on arms to get attention, a behavior that we are working with her to improve. Robyn loves food and will eat anything you put in front of her.

Robyn is selective about dogs. With our rescue staff under supervision she has done great with every dog she's been introduced to. She is happy and playful and eager to engage. In her home she did not get along with the other dog. Overall fit will be important.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: We have estimated Robyn's birthday at 12/23/2019. Robyn was found as a stray. This is purely an estimate based on her overall health and condition.

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.

animal.description:
Meet Milano!
Have you ever met someone that makes your world brighter just by knowing them?? If not maybe you should meet me...my name is Milano and I am an amazing puppy with a big story. You see I had 3 siblings and when they were rescued I ran away and was not found till I was 6 months old...broken leg and skinny I had never known a humans love...well you would never know that's how I grew up because I am the happiest, most friendly puppy you will meet!! I am crate trained and house broken. In my foster home I live with kitties and other dogs and I love them all. My leg has healed and playing in my favorite thing to do. I LOVE toys and like to empty all the toy baskets. I bring them to bed, outside, on the couch wherever I can put them I surround myself with toys. I have tons of energy and love to run in the yard. I do worry if I can't see you outside so my foster mom is always outside with me so I never go looking for her where I am not supposed to. I am learning how to listen, sit and stay but my puppy energy gets the best of me sometimes. I am super smart and want to please you. I am so thankful to be in a warm home and would love to have my own forever family. My foster mom says I am one of those dogs you meet and never forget. I dive into your body to snuggle and sleep on my back in bed. And did I mention how handsome I am?? I'm ready and waiting for your application...can't wait to meet you. Submit your applications online at: https://oneloveanimalrescue.com/pre-adoption-application/

**WE ONLY DO HOME VISITS FOR ADOPTIONS NEAR BROWARD & PALM BEACH COUNTIES**

Check our New Years' baby, Rockwell ChiPoo (Chihuahua Poodle) He is lively and fun. He does take time to accept new people and will bark BUT baby talk works well to soothe him. He is 2 and a half years old and 10 pounds. He may not be totally hypoallergenic so if you have allergies to dogs, he won't be a match. Rockwell needs an adult home that will help him through his initial fear then he will give hugs to ask for attention. He comes around to love within an hour and he does NOT bite except at the vet when he is held down. Rockwell needs more work on socialization with new people. 

He does bark, so if you are in a high-rise situation where you would be passing people all the time and you are not experienced with how to help him overcome his fears, then Rockwell is not for you. He thinks he is going to be hurt so this may take a while for him to get over his fear. He is loving and cuddly once he trusts you but every new person, Rockwell will go through this fear until he is properly desensitized. You will need to continue with nonaggressive training in order for him to have a peaceful life and not incidents of him getting into danger! He is always following you around and instantly rolls over for belly rubs! 

He sleeps next to you as you with a subtle smile of appreciation. If you are looking for a little buddy, please check Rockwell! Rockwell's adoption fee is $350 to go towards his vetting (vaccines, spay/neuter, heartworm/Ehrlichia/Lyme test, fecal test, pre-op blood work, dental cleaning, and microchip as well as grooming if needed). If you are interested please fill out the adoption application For additional information regarding our adoption process, please check our FAQ's Page. 

 *All dogs in the care of Get a Life Pet Rescue live in loving foster homes while waiting for their perfect match. They don't live in cages or crates (unless there is a medical reason to do so.) They are treated as family pets while in our care. * All dogs in our care are fed premium brand holistic food as well as supplements and vitamins specific to each dog's needs. 

We don't buy inexpensive bulk dry kibble, our rescues are fed premium wet food diets as part of a comprehensive rehabilitation program to ensure maximum health.*All of our rescues receive complete quality vetting including full dental cleaning with pre-op bloodwork, spay/neuter, vaccines, and grooming. Dogs in need of specialized medicine will be seen by specialists, such as full cardiac workups, ophthalmologist visits, all suspicious lumps, and bumps are biopsied, and every medical need is transparent to potential adopters. *Once you adopt from Get a Life Pet Rescue, you become part of our compassionate family and we are here for you if a problem with your precious dog arises.

Contact 954-629-2445 or getalifepetrescue11@gmail.com
