animal.description:
For up-to-date info like events, closings, new animals, success stories please LIKE Manchester Animal Shelter on Facebook!

Gypsy and Tyson...A Bonded Pair!!!

Gypsy is a white 12 year old female Pittie mix weighing 65lbs. She is bonded to her brother Tyson. Tyson is a brown 5 year old male Pittie mix weighing 75lbs. 

Gypsy and Tyson have been together their whole lives. Both of their owners passed away recently, leaving them alone. Family feared they would be separated if they stayed in NC, so they made the big trip to NH in hopes of finding their furever home together. Let's hope their trip was worth it! 

Gypsy is a spunky lady full of life and energy! She's a go getter! She loves life and everything it has to offer. She's very social and loves to know everything that's going on. :) She is the more independent one of the two.  

Tyson is a calm, gentle lover. He likes the quieter, finer things in life; a nice walk, a snuggle on the couch watching TV, a nice massage ;)...He can be quite silly, too and is a blast to play with! 

These 2 cuties will need to be adopted together. They would do best in a home with children 12+ years old. If you would like to fill out an application please email canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org 


Adoption fee is based on age:
Puppies 8 weeks through 7 months are $400
Dogs 8 months through 7 years are $325
Senior dogs over 8 years are $125 
Seniors for Seniors (Seniors 65+ adopting over 8 years): $75

All adoptable dogs are spayed and neutered, have age and time appropriate vaccines, microchipped and heartworm tested. Other medical care provided might include treatments for fleas, ear mites, dental work or infections or other medical conditions. Additional vaccinations and medical care (including puppies Rabies shots if adopted at under 12 weeks of age) will be the responsibility of the adopter.

If you have questions you can call our office at 603.628.3544. To request an application, please email canines@manchesteranimalshelter.org
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Note: As with all of our dogs, we strongly recommend obedience classes for new owner and dog to create a life-long bond with the adopted dog based on trust, respect, and rewarding training experiences. Our shelter dogs are strays and we observe and assess their behavior at the shelter which may be somewhat different in a home environment.
animal.name: Gypsy and Tyson...We Are A Bonded Pair!

animal.description:
Name: ?Cody?
Age, Weight Gender: 2 yrs, 65lb male
Dog friendly/required?: no? / no
Cat Friendly: NO!
Fenced yard required?: Yes
Housetrained: getting there...
Crate trained: Yes
Children: 10+
Temperament: medium energy / loves humans / no food or toy aggression 
Cody is hypersensitive to other dogs but it is possible for him to live with another dog. It will take time for him to accept and feel safe with any other dog in the house. It took us 2 weeks before Cody could interact with our 2 labs without a gate between them. Based on his behavior and scars on his backend lead us to believe he didn’t have good interactions with other dogs before being picked up as a stray. If a potential adopter has a dog they must understand Cody will need time and patience before he will be okay with their dog. The other dog will need to be laid back and young since Cody can be quite annoying sometimes with play. He’s still learning social skills and how to play without being so rough. Our 2 have adjusted to his play and let him know when enough is enough. Our female, Daisy, is the alpha and Cody does well with her with no aggression. Taking a walk is a real struggle. He PULLS and is very strong. Now that he’s done chilling out from the last HW injections we will start taking some walks to see if we can get any improvement. Stairs are still a challenge. He wants nothing to do with 5 or more steps. We’re still working on house training. He wandered into another part of the house this week and peed. ???? Meal time is a joy now that Cody doesn’t try to make a seat for himself at the table. He now lays down next to us while we eat with no interest. He hasn’t counter surfed in awhile either. He’s interested and will put his nose up to smell but hasn’t tried to get anything in weeks. Crate time is a breeze and enters on command! He does have a prey drive so no small animals in the household for him. This boy has improved so much but does need more training. He will make a great companion for a family that is dog savvy and willing to continue training. It’s not his fault he only knew how to survive on the streets and fend for himself. ? Cody ?

animal.description:
We received a call from social services in Alabama about a group of dogs in serious trouble. The owner had gotten sick and had to go to the hospital. She asked someone to go and feed her dogs for her. The stench and filth were unbearable. She and these dogs were living in conditions that are hard to imagine. She has became a ward of the state and her dogs were surrendered to us. We thought that we had found Leo his forever home but he was so happy to have a home where he was loved that he became protective of his new owner. Sadly, this was more than she wanted to deal with so she returned him to us. He needs someone who understands that his greatest fear is being abandoned by those he loves. Please help us find him a forever home! 

COMPLETED APPLICATIONS TAKE PRECEDENCE OVER INQUIRIES! IF you are interested in adopting, the FIRST step is to complete an application! Please email for an Application or copy and paste the following URL: 

https://fs26.formsite.com/nogreaterlove/form2/index.html 

Upon receipt of your application, the rescuer and foster in AL will contact you so you can ask any specific questions you may have! If there is more than one decision maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement! 

 Adoption Donation: Unless otherwise stated in the pet's bio, our standard adoption fee is $395 which covers age appropriate vaccines (DHPP vax) and (Rabies vax if 12 weeks and older), utd on flea/tick prevention and heartworm prevention, worming, heartworm test @ age 6 months or older, microchip, fostering costs and health certificate.

Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

We do not adopt to anyone under the age of 21

animal.description:
Name: Bella

Age: 4 years old

Gender: Female

Breed: German Shepherd/Terrier Mix

Weight: 39 lbs

Dog friendly: Shy around dogs

Cat friendly: unknown, testing available upon request.

Child friendly: Yes, older, kind, gentle school-aged kids 5+ years

House trained: Yes

Crate trained: in progress

Energy level: Mild

Temperament: Sweet, Gentle, Loving, Timid, Shy, Protective
Requirement: Not apartment appropriate

Adoption Fee: $375+tax

To adopt, go to:
www.mendingspirits.org/apply-to-adopt.html

From the Foster Family:

We have come a long way in such a small time! Bella was an extremely

shy girl when we first started fostering her. She was timid and put

her head down in fear and shame. She is now understanding what it

means to be loved and to live in a safe place. Bella is a quick

learner and motivated by hugs. All you have to do is tell her that

she is a good girl and she gets her tail wagging in accomplishment.

She leaves treats behind for loving attention. This girl would do well

as a companion, cuddle buddy, and protector. She is playful and

"cat-like" in the way she paws at things. Bella is the most deserving

of your love and kindness, and will be able to accomplish so many

things as she wants to please, she will just need some encouragement

and a lot of patience until she feels comfortable enough to be ready

to train.

About Me:

Hello, I am Bella! I am kinda shy at first, and I've begun to trust

humans again. I love to know where my five foster humans are at all

times. If one of them leaves, I notice and feel a little sad. I like

to follow and investigate where everyone is and I'm especially happy

when everyone is together-it makes my job a lot easier! I am trying

to get used to my kennel, but I would much rather lay around nearby

you. My heart is getting filled a little more each day with a lot of

encouragement and patience from my foster family. I am happy now, I

wag my tail, smile, and do all sorts of things that make my foster

family laugh. I have some toys that I love and I pretend are the only

mine, but I only like to play this game! I really am a great girl and

want to be your best friend!

animal.description:
? #845 - Gus | COMING SOON & ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS

Meet Gus! This 7-8 year old has had a lot of overcome and is making progress every day.

Gus was found by a family in the rural Panhandle of Texas. Gus was all alone and no owners were found. When Gus was rescued he got a nice bath and we expect to see his coat get shiny as he continues to adjust to good nutrition and care. Due to being alone for so long, Gus is shy. He wasn't used to being part of a family and everything was scary. In the time he's been in rescue, he's learned that humans can be kind and caring. We can't blame the guy for being a bit skeptical after what he's been through.

Gus LOVES his crate and enjoys spending time relaxing and snuggling. He would prefer a quiet home that's calm and caring. Because he has been through a lot, we recommend we be placed in a home without other pets. Gus likes to learn and would benefit from continued education. He is also proud to share he has learned how to use the doggie door!

Gus just wants a home that will love him. Does Gus sound like your guy? Fill out an application to adopt now!

BCRRT is a Texas based rescue with fosters in TX and OK. Our adoption areas are TX, OK and surrounding states. We do not allow shipping/transport of dogs to other states. If you are interested and would like to apply please visit: https://bcrrt.com/adoption/ and fill out an application form.

We are working on taking treats easily and waiting for food but it’s been very difficult for him. Ace likes cuddling before bed, food, walks, playing with his canine siblings and water. animal.description:
If you are interested in Foster, please fill out an adoption application at www.mdgsprescue.org. We rarely respond to messages sent via PetFinder, so if you have a question, please fill out the contact form on our website. Thanks!

Foster is a beautiful solid black, 1 year old, male Pointer mix who might be part kangaroo. He can jump 5 feet from a standing position and uses his vertical when he meets new people, when he wants inside, or when his people come home. He loves everyone he meets including kids. He currently lives with a 4 year old and a 9 year old and does great with both. Any kids in his forever family will need to be large dog savvy given his exuberance and size. 


Foster weighs in around 60 pounds, but is tall and skinny. Once he gets to a healthy weight he'll probably be closer to 70 pounds. Due to his near constant motion he would do best with a family that has another large active dog. He loves to wrestle and play chase and be outside as long as he has a playmate. He is not particularly dominant or submissive, but does test boundaries like most young dogs. He is currently doing well in a home with a large 2 year old male and 1 year old female.

Foster has slept well crated and with his 9 year old foster kid. When crated he whines/barks intermittently for a minute or two then settles down. He's mostly house trained and only has the occasional accident. He knows "sit", "no", and comes when he can tell you want him. He's a quick study, very responsive and even listens to commands from the kids. He isn't much of a barker, but does bark when he gets super excited, like waiting for meal time. He isn't terrible on a leash but does need work on leash manners.

Other items of interest about Foster: He wasn't fazed by the NYE fireworks. He doesn't seem to care to play with balls or toys.He gives dainty kisses but is the sloppiest drinkier. He doesn't like baths. He hasn't tried to escape out the front door or over the fence, but will need 6ft fencing or efencing. Not sure if he's oblivious or doesn't care, but he hasn't shown interest in squirrels or birds. He's all over the place in the car and needs to be tethered or crated.

Foster is a very sweet young guy who is looking forward to finding an active forever family. He is already neutered and scheduled for his vaccinations 1/14. He is being fostered in Severna Park, MD. Please fill out an adoption application if Foster interests you!

animal.description:
If you are interested in Nitro, please fill out an application at www.mdgsprescue.org. We rarely respond to messages sent via PetFinder. Thanks!

Meet Nitro!! He is a handsome loving 8 year old boy.  Nitro is fully house trained and loves any chance to snuggle next to you or under a blanket. He is a big boy but he doesn’t try and jump up on you when he plays.
 
He definitely could use some more training on a leash as he does pull. He is quite strong so paying attention on walks is important as He will pull when he sees a bird or squirrel. He has no problem meeting people/dogs on or off leash. He is chatty though so he barks and whines in excitement. He is a neat drinker and eater and hardly sheds at all.

 Nitro does love to run around and  is an agile climber, 4-5 ft high wire gauge fencing is not an option so he requires a yard with secure, solid 6-ft fencing or efencing. He definitely loves his walks and running outside. Nitro is not a fan of car rides so this will require more work to make him comfortable.

He will do better in a home where he can have his family with him. Leaving him does cause him stress. He will go in a crate but is not a fan of it at all. He has been left out not crated for short intervals and has done fine. He doesn’t touch anything that is not his. He shows a lot of improvement when we practice leaving to help him gain his confidence.

Nitro is so lovable and willing to please. He is a great dog! Nitro is being fostered in Baltimore, MD. If you are interested, please fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
If you are interested in Petey, please fill out an application at www.mdgsprescue.org. We rarely respond to messages via PetFinder so if you have a question, please fill out the contact form on our webpage. Thanks!

Petey is a handsome neutered 10 year old male GSP, weighing 50lbs. Petey was surrendered to rescue when his owner's living situation changed. 


Petey loves the children in his foster home. He is a spunky dog who is quite happy hanging by your side or going on adventures. He walks well on a leash and rides beautifully in the car. Petey is house broken and working on his obedience. Petey loves toys and has a drive for fetch just as strong as a young pointer. Petey is happy to play fetch until your arm falls off! Petey sleeps happily on a dog bed at night and does not try to steal the bed if you have to get up.


Petey is currently in 6ft fencing and doing well. Due to his prey-drive Petey should not live with cats (he sometimes gets over excited and points the scotty dog door stopper at his foster's house)! Rescue has not observed Petey around dogs, but he seemed ok with them when he was at the vet. Any introductions would need to be controlled and not rushed to see how Petey does.


Petey is being fostered in Washington, DC and is patiently waiting for his forever home. If he interests you, please fill out an adoption application.

Adoption fee: $425
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. Breed: One of a kind

Weight: 72

When we say, "age is nothing but a number" we are referring to our bouncy boy MONGO! You wouldn't know this sweet boy's age with his playful and sweet personality! If you are looking for the cutest social butterfly, Mongo is the dog for you

Before you can adopt, please complete an adoption application on our website at pawscrossedny.org/dog-adoption-application! Once your application is approved, you will be able to call to schedule an appointment. If you have any questions, please email us at adoptions@pawscrossedny.org for more information. Please understand that we cannot hold any pets. All adoptions are done on a first come, first adopt basis for approved applicants.

The Shelter software system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable so for most of our dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We encourage you to select your new companion by considering each dog's individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on a breed label that is only a guess.

animal.description:
Autumn is an 8-week-old mixed breed rescued from a high-kill shelter. This dog is current on vaccinations, microchipped, and spayed/neutered. This puppy is currently in foster care learning home etiquette, kennel training, and housebreaking. We would love for you to meet this puppy and see if it might be a good fit for your home. 

The first step to adoption is completing an adoption application on our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org. Pending approval, your application is valid for 1 year, and you will be eligible to request a hold on an individual animal. The hold does not require that you adopt the animal, but ensures you get to meet and make an adoption decision prior to other applicants. Hold times cannot exceed 5 days. Also pending approval, you will be able to acquire foster home contact information, so you inquire on personalities of specific animals.

***COVID-19 Update: While we typically host weekly Saturday adoption events, in order to follow the CDC's recommendation for COVID-19 protocols, we will be suspending our weekly Saturday adoption events until given the clear. Adoptions for individual animals will occur by private adoption appointment and/or adoption handoff. Appointments and handoffs are scheduled pending staff, foster home, and vetting schedules. Because we are 100% foster-based, adoption appointments and handoffs are only offered for individual animals. When adopting at an appointment, please be aware that you will be taking the animal home that day. We can not hold animals to be picked up at a later date.

Due to CDC's recommended COVID-19 protocols, we are highly encouraging foster homes and adopters to speak with one another via phone or video chat to ensure compatible matches and limit in-person contact. If meeting in person, our foster homes are encouraged to wear masks, socially distance, and choose an outdoor meeting spot. Should you want to proceed forward with the adoption, all adoption paperwork, medical records, and adoption fees are to be completed electronically. Quick and low-contact animal handoff is also being encouraged amongst foster homes and adopters. As always, we include a one-week trial period with all our adoptions. ***

Please note, we do not have the ability to process adoption applications at our adoption events, so please plan accordingly. If an application is submitted past 5pm on Monday-Thursday, it will begin review the following day. If submitted on Friday-Sunday, it will begin review on Monday. It takes approximately 48-72 hours for an application to be processed.

For additional questions regarding meeting this dog please contact us via text/email at 970.699.6772, or contact@bounceanimalrescue.org. We apologize for any inconvenience, but due to a high volume of inquiries, calls and voicemails regarding adoption will not be returned.

Thank you for choosing adoption! If you would like more information on our organization please visit our website at www.bounceanimalrescue.org.

animal.description:
Name: Hobbit (nickname Bubba)
Breed: Husky 
Age: 2 years
Neutered Male

Hobbit is a sweetheart with a gentle and playful soul. He has most certainly had a hard time in his life. But also some really good ones. He was rescued from a kill shelter. He is shy of strangers at first but comes around quickly. Just a good scratch or a nice treat and your his new best friend. He is more scared of men than women, but he does come around after a few gentle words and lots of hugs/pets lol. He loves to be hugged and petted. He loves going for walks or runs. He is high energy (like all huskies). He is leash-trained, house-trained and crate-trained. He bathes well and brushes great. He rides well in the car. He is learning basic commends well and enjoys the attention. He is great with other dogs, but not with cats. He should be fine with kids, he's so gentle. He loves treats and toys. He really likes to be with his people. He is a talker but not a barker and will have whole conversations with you. He would love an active family to play with and show him that there are good people in the world too. He'd make a great agility dog because he is so smart, willing to please and has some awesome moves lol.

DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE VOLUNTEER IN CHARGE OF THE RESCUE EMAIL IS OUT WITH COVID PLEASE SEND ALL INQUIRIES TO THE FOSTER MOM JENNY AT foster.pups@yahoo.com

All of our dogs listed are in foster homes. Please email or call for price and more information on the gorgeous dog. Adoption fee includes spay/neuter and up-to-date shots. Adoption fees also help us buy food, medicine, and other expenses for our animals. If you have any questions, please contact Last Hope Cat Kingdom  at friends@lasthopecatkingdom.org.

animal.description:
I'm Paloma, but I also listen to the name Potato!

I originally came to Paws it Forward over 7 years ago. At that time I was terrified of humans and had a very rough start to life. I was lucky enough to find my family and I was able to learn that I actually love humans! Unfortunately, lately I had been getting into disagreements with my senior K9 sibling and my humans had to make the difficult decision to put me back into Paws it Fowards care. 

My ideal home would be one where I am the only pet as I can get very jealous when another pet is getting my humans attention. I also can be protective over my food as I don't like to share! 

My people say I am a sweet soul at heart. I am happy to go for walks or snuggle on the couch, whatever my human would like me to do with them, I will be right there by their side! I enjoy having older kids around (10+) to play with and love. I can still be timid around some humans sometimes so I would need a family that has patience with me. However, I will be very loyal to my people and give them my undying loyalty and love once I am comfortable around them. 

I love being outside and do great on a leash. I even like this white stuff on the ground! I also enjoy going for car rides because it usually means I get to be with my human and go somewhere exciting. I am quiet in the house and you only hear from me when I'm feeling happy. I am very obedient and listen to what my humans say. 

A note from my current foster mom, "If you are allergic to bees, this is your dog! Paloma is passionate about hunting bees in mid air. She also makes us laugh and does a great impression of jumping goats."

I was lucky enough to find a great family once, I know my next and final family is out there patiently waiting for me to come into their life! 

If you are interested in adopting me, please fill out an application on our website www.pawsitforward.org

My adoption fee is $350

She's an absolute delight Due to their tiny sizes, it would be best if Rue and Brenda go to a home with no small children. Older responsible ones would be okay. If you're looking for a precious pair of sweet housetrained girls to add to your family and share life with, please submit an adoption application for Brenda and Rue. They would love you more than you might ever imagine

animal.description:
UPDATE as of Jan 30th: Because of considerable interest in this dog, we are no longer accepting new applications.

Well hello, my name is Simon! And I’m quite a catch if I do say so myself. I’m a 1-year-old, 50-ish pound Shepherd mix, and I already can’t wait to meet you.
 
I LOVE meeting humans and other dogs. Sometimes I get a little carried away though and jump up to show you just how happy I am to meet you. But I’m totally willing to work on that. Besides meeting new people and animals, I really love to play with toys and chew on bones. I do better with toys that are super durable because I’ve set actual records for destroying plush toys in seconds. And I get really excited when my people play with me. Sometimes I nip a little when I get too excited, so it might be best if my new family doesn’t have really young humans--I wouldn’t want to scare anyone.
 
It may sound like I’m bragging, but I am a really great houseguest. I’m totally housebroken, and if I have to go potty, I’ll come up and pester you to let you know it’s time to go out. I’ll sleep in a crate if you want me to, although I have a whole room to myself at my foster home, and I love having a little space at night. During the day, I’ll happily nap at your side wherever you are. I also love to go for walks or play outside.  Fair warning, I love meeting other humans on my walks, but I’m very polite about it. Sometimes I pull when I see a rabbit or a squirrel, but mostly, I’m really good on my leash. My foster family says I’m a total goofball with a lot of energy. I love to burn off my energy on walks or running around the yard, and then I’m very content snuggling by your side or with my head in your lap. And if you give me tummy rubs, I’ll be the happiest boy ever.
 
My ideal home would have a fenced yard and would be cat free. Honestly, I love cats and would chase them around the house all day long, but my foster mom tells me that cats don’t really like that so I should probably not have the temptation.  
 
So, what do you think? Are we a match made in heaven? I sure hope so. If you agree, you know what to do! Can’t wait to meet you!

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description: Hi there! Thanks so much for taking a look at me. I'm a sweet girl who has loads of energy and lots of love to give!! I do pull slightly on my leash when out for a walk, but I promise, let me calm down and I will walk a bit better. I LOVE to be with or near my handlers, but I get so excited!! I run around, I jump and I'm just all over the place, only because of how excited I am. Please take that into consideration, that I do need help learning not to jump on my hoomans! Again, because of my excitement I would recommend allowing me to calm down before proceeding with handling or petting; teaches good behavior! If you need help in that field, please feel free to ask these people taking good care of me! I love to play with my handlers as well, but because of my excitement level and arousal, I'd recommend a home with children no younger than 10, just because of how hyper I can be! I love to play with squeaky toys, but if you want it back I'm going to need something in exchange! So, I currently know sit and because I love treats, maybe I can learn new tricks? Although, if you're going to feed my treats I would recommend no tiny fingers! I take a little roughly. :( Now dogs, they seem soo cool! I get so excited that I will pull to greet them and greet them in their face! Which may come off a bit rude, so allow me to calm down and after I'm calm, I will say hi to them respectfully. I can't help it! I'm just so excited. Overall, I would recommend myself in an active home helping me learn new behaviors and a home dedicated to training. I hope to meet you soon!

animal.description:
At 6 weeks old Athena was attacked by another dog and left without vet care for nearly a week. Her wound swelled up and her eye was nearly closed shut when we got her and her siblings, and finally, she is ready for her forever home.
Athena was born on 10/30/20 and is a lovable, spunky girl. She will likely be medium sized full grown, on the lower side around 30 pounds or so. 
Athena loves to play dress up, snuggle, and run around with her sister, who is almost fully recovered as well. 
She is up to date, microchipped and fully dewormed. Her bite marks and wounds are a thing of the past and give adorable character to her, she has never let what happened to her stop her.

Athena is forever home ready and an example of the amazing things rescue can do for our animals who need us the most

Please note: as with most rescue puppies, we have no way to guarantee this puppy’s breed or size potential. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2021 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

animal.description:
***Thank you for your interest in Magnificent Mutts and Meows. We hope everyone is saying safe during this challenging time. Due to the current regulations set forth by Governor Pritzker on group gatherings we will not be having adoption events until further notice. As an all foster based rescue this means that all meets will be by appointment only. Your whole family must be available to attend the meet as there will be no second meets scheduled to help limit contact between our team and the public. To help streamline the process please make sure your current pets are up to date, you have landlord/HOA approval, and that you are prepared to take the dog home with you immediately before submitting an application. Thank you & Please stay safe!***

Sandy is a sweet girl who takes time to warm up to new people. She likes the company of children but does get startled when they run or jump so any children in the home should be well behaved and dog savvy. Sandy came into our rescue with her pups and is still learning she is now safe. She appreciates having a cozy spot to retreat to when needed but after a short time to regroup she returns for attention and treats. She loves squeaky toys and to snuggle up to her human while watching TV. She bonds to her person quickly and wants to be with them all the time so she would make a great companion! Sandy gets along with dogs, but dog in the home should be calmer to help ease her nerves as well. A quiet patient home is needed and we are certain with some time to open up she will be a life long best friend to whomever is the lucky person to adopt her!

If you are interested in adoption, please complete the Application to Adopt which you can find on our website (
www.magnificentmutts.org
) No phone calls please. Emails only.

animal.description:
Meet Milly a.k.a Milady! She is a 4 year old, 45 pound, female, Belgian Malinois/Labrador Mix. We think Milly is just the prettiest dog in town! She will win your heart over the second you meet her with a gentle hand lick and her soulful eyes. Once she settles into a new place she will let her personality sparkle. Her foster mom lovingly called her a “prancing reindeer” as she loves to hop around the house and play with her toys when she is excited and happy. After some playtime or a nice walk, Milly loves to curl up in her dog bed or on the couch for a nice snooze. If you are settling in for movie night you better be ready to share your lap as Milly loves to lay down and rest her head on her person. She is a very quick leaner and is fully potty trained! She will sleep through the night in her dog bed and doesn’t require a crate. She is excellent in the car for long rides… she will climb in on her own and won’t make a peep from the backseat. Milly goes with the flow very well. 

Milly is looking for an adult only home with no young children, no other dogs, and a backyard. Milly can be selective about other dogs when on her leash, so needs a home outside of the city and although she can have dog friends, she does better being the only pet in the home. Are you the magical home Milly can finally call her own?! Submit your application for this gem today! 

No urban homes, other pets, or kids! Milly is looking for a backyard in her forever home. 

Milly is spayed and up to date on her vaccinations. For more information about her, please fill out an application at www.ALRcares.com and email Grace@alrcares.com.  We schedule meet and greets for approved adopters only, an application is the first step in our approval process. Thank you!

animal.description:
I'm Arlo. I'm a 1 year old Boxer mix.  I am really curious and like to watch what my foster family is doing.  My little doggy foster sister taught me how much fun running around and rolling in the snow can be.  We burn off energy together and then take naps inside.  I like to lay in the sun, but also spend time in a doggy bed where I can keep an eye on my family.  I use the time outside to take care of business.  I haven't had any accidents inside.  I really love cuddling and will sneak a kiss when you're not watching.  I really like food.  My foster dad says that makes me easier to train.  I'm pretty good at sitting but sometimes I need to sit for longer than I really want to.  When it's time for bed, I go right into my crate.  I sleep through the night without a sound, which is more than I can say for my foster sister.  She's good at playing though, she even pulled me across the carpet playing tug.  She shares her squeaky toys and bones with me, too.  I love being scratched on the head and behind the ears. I've done really well with car rides, too.  If you're looking for a loving companion, I'm your guy!

If you would like to be considered as a potential adopter for one of our great dogs, please go to our website- www.luckymuttsrescue.org and submit an application. Our application process includes landlord approval and vet checks. Please make sure all of your information is current and accurate, including a valid email address and phone numbers. Inaccuracies and/or incomplete data will delay and/or cancel your application.  We strive to process all applications in a timely manner, but with the high volume of applications we are receiving, it is taking anywhere from 1-3 weeks.  You may be contacted via email if there are concerns or questions.  Once all of your information is reviewed and if your application is approved, you will be notified via email.  Submitting an application and receiving an approval does not guarantee you will be adopting the dog you applied for.  Once you move to the meet and greet process, you will be contacted by the foster family to further discuss the dog, and answer questions you may have, and if applicable, a meet and greet will be set up at our adoption center.   Meet and greets are only set up with approved applicants, and we require all members in the household to be present, as well as any current dogs in the home. 

Current Adoption Fees Are:
$400+tax for puppies to 3 years old
$350+tax for ages 4-7
$250+tax for ages 8 and up
Bonded pairs vary

The adoption fee covers spay/neuter, up to date age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, general deworming, heartworm test, (if over 6  months) and a certified veterinary inspection. Please be aware, listed dog breeds are based on information provided and cannot be guaranteed.  Submitting an application for a particular dog does not guarantee that you will be the applicant chosen, we receive several applications for each dog. Our adopters are picked based on the needs of the dog, and the home we feel with best fit based on your responses to our application, vet information and landlord requirements.   Approved applicants not chosen for the dog you applied for, will be in active status for a period of six months.  We encourage you to watch Petfinder, Facebook and our website for upcoming dogs.  Should you see a dog that interests you, please send us a Facebook message or an email with your approval number.  Please be patient with us, as Lucky Mutts Rescue is run strictly by volunteers and many of us work full time jobs, have families and also foster dogs. Thank you for considering Lucky Mutts Rescue for your next furry family member!

animal.description:
Found in a forest, beautiful May is ready for some spoiling. This 1-year-old Great Pyrenees mix loves to be with her people, just looking for comfort and companionship.

Housebroken and crate-trained, May’s house manners are good — she rarely barks and doesn’t chew inappropriately. She’s looking for a quiet household (no loud noises, no other dogs, just quiet consistency) where she can build up her trust. May is not a big fan of the leash or of car rides. She loves hanging out in a snowy backyard.

May will do best as the only dog in a home, but at 85 pounds of fluff, she is all the dog you’ll need! She is loving and gentle with the child at her foster home. 

If you have a quiet home and are looking for a mellow solo dog to be your best friend, come meet May.

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description: Recommended an experienced home with kids age 12 and up who are gentle and respectful. Lottie is a moderate energy teenager at an awkward age. She sometimes presents as serious and somewhat judgy as she is figuring out her place in the world. Other times she presents as a silly, playful youngster. She is moderately social, mostly tolerant of handling and pulls on leash. She shows no interest in toys at this time, but hopefully she will loosen up and enjoy them soon. In the assessment when presented with a particularly yummy bowl of food she settled into enjoying it. She refused to budge from it despite a hard push from a fake hand. No other escalation shown. So we instigated a trade out upgrade as a training exercise. She participated in this exercise 3 times as an interruption of her meal and we let her finish the bowl. The last step into her food area resulted in a freeze and solid direct eye contact. We carefully resumed the last trade out for the bowl. Continuing this protocol is a must, in addition to a leadership training policy called nothing in life is for free. Lottie needs an experienced leadership home with rules dedicated to training and exercise. NOT CATS Dog to dog - 1st encounter: Met a medium sized calm mature male dog where she mostly ignored him and looked through him mainly checking out the environment. A few times briefly when in close proximity she would focus on him with pilo and a slight freeze before resuming ignoring him. A few days later, 2nd encounter: An introduction was done with a more confident, bolder adult male Pittie. She became pilo erect from afar, pulling towards, barking and general trash talking. Wanted to meet as an equal and rather full of herself. On closer encounter she was startled when he called her on it and hovered over her (ranking) and sniffing invasively. She finally (caved in her posturing) gave a light tail wag, became playful and jumped on the handler multiple times. So when confronted with a stronger personality she allowed invasive sniffing without correcting or avoiding- then went and jumped on handler out of mouthy arousal. She jumps excessively. In summary: Someday over the next year of learning she will be a high ranking female with dogs. Guiding her successfully through this period of learning will be formative in her adult personality to be cognizant of proper dog diplomacy and not become a bully. No off leash venues or multiple dog settings recommended.

animal.description:
MEET BUDDY CHANCE!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4084697.

Unfortunately, this is Buddy Chance's second time at the shelter and no one can understand why. He's a great dog that loves to go for a walk. He loves to play with toys in the play yard and he's an affectionate boy that will come up to you for pets. He loves his treats and will "sit" for them. He doesn't react to the other dogs in their kennels or when he sees them on the trail going for a walk.

Buddy Chance is starting to have a hard time in his kennel and has been observed jumping up to see the neighboring dog. He needs a new home soon where his family will play with toys with him and take him for a walk. If you think Buddy Chance would be a good fit in your home, please bring the family and come and meet him today! If you have any other dogs at home, please bring them with you to make sure it will be a good fit.

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Jenny Cope (giveadogahome@live.com) for more information about this pet.

Be sure to read ALL information provided.

A PET IS FOR LIFE -
THINK ABOUT THE INVESTMENT!

NOAH was saved from a high kill shelter in Texas where dogs often have only 3 days to be saved. NOAH is neutered rabies, core vaccines, heartworm/tick disease tested negative for all. He is de-wormed, monthly preventatives and microchipped. At the time of rescue in the middle of January 2021, he weighed around 24.00 pounds and has an estimated date of birth 24 April 2020

. We cannot say for sure what breed he is, so we expect families to do their own research on his look and size and decide what breed you think she is and if you have the lifestyle suitable for his needs.

When Noah arrived at the rescue on 15 January he was in a double kennel with a few other dogs his age and had a great time playing and wrestling in the outside run, then when done playing, they would cuddle up on the elevated dog bed and recharge their batteries for their next play session.

With most dogs being adopted, Noah and the dogs still here have been relocated to the communal area where they have access to a large secure fenced in area where they are loving playing in the snow and enjoying the cooler weather. He does jump up as with all rescues wanting to get some attention, but this is easily fixed with training and he is very responsive.

Noah is a medium sized dog, full of love, energy and affection, he loves to get his ears scratched and his belly rubbed. We are not able to say how he is around cats or livestock and so it is up to families to be prepared to work through any potential issues.

Noah is a high energy dog so we are only looking for families who already have the lifestyle to incorporate this handsome boy into that life. A family that understands the importance of training and mental stimulation along with the physical needs of this young pup who will take him and ensure he is given lots of adventure and fun.

More pictures and possible video's can be found on his page on the rescue website.

All dogs use dog doors to go out and do their business or to enjoy the cool, fresh weather in their dog runs or communal areas. We cannot say if a dog is house-trained, however, we expect families to understand that all dogs need a transition period and accidents could happen and training is most definitely needed.

You MUST understand that dogs need time to decompress and adapt to their new environment and home. It is a HUGE transition they make from the kill shelter, being vetted, on transport for 3 days and arriving in Maine where the temperature and such is very different to what they have only known. In rescue there is what is known as the "3 Point Rule" Days 1-3 your dog is stressed, anxious, confused as to where they are now. Weeks 1-3 your dog is adjusting, settling in, learning things. At the 3 month point, your dog understands they are home, and have built up a trusting relationship where they feel loved and secure.

All dogs are fed Rachael Ray Nutrish PEAK Natural Dry Dog Food, Grain Free Western Grasslands Recipe with Bison. Rachael Ray Nutrish Peak Dog Food receives the Dog Food Advisor's second-highest tier rating of 4.5 stars.

NOAH is available for adoption for an adoption fee of $550

This fee is not negotiable and is used to cover the rescue costs of pulling, vetting, health certificate, transport from Texas to Maine, monthly preventatives, supplements, food, general day to day cost of running a brick and mortar rescue and anything else that is needed. Canadian adopters need to know that customs charge 15% taxes when entering into Canada.

Due to borders being closed, it is up to families to call the US and Canadian borders to find the current details on border crossing. Animal Welfare is deemed essential in the US, but quarantine rules entering back into Canada must be followed.

If you feel that you have the heart and home to give this precious soul a wonderful life, please go to our website, under the ADOPTION INFO tab, complete, then submit the APPLICATION. Our process takes around 1-2 days, and ensuring your references are aware that we will be calling, could speed up the process. Once you have been approved, we discuss any questions in regards to the dog you are wanting to adopt, then you complete and submit the contract, make payment and then we can work out the pick up / transport arrangements.

Please do NOT submit an application if you are not looking to take home a new best friend within the next few weeks.

https://www.giveadogahome-sanantonio.org/forms/form?formid=5838

ALL Dogs are LOCATED AT THE RESCUE IN SEBEC, MAINE. We post in various states along the east coast and Canada where we have had lots of successful adoptions to enable more exposure for these beautiful saved souls. Families will need to be prepared to travel to the rescue to meet and take home their new best friend. Sebec is located just outside the towns of Dover-Foxcroft and Milo (approx 8 miles) and approx 45 miles from Bangor. There are also lots of hotels, motels, pet friendly accommodations and wonderful camp-sites for the more adventurous families and what a great way to get to know your new best friend.

Click here to watch a video of NOAH.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Jenny Cope (giveadogahome@live.com) for more information about this pet.

Be sure to read ALL information provided.

A PET IS FOR LIFE -
THINK ABOUT THE INVESTMENT!

AUBREY was saved from a high kill shelter in Texas where dogs often have only 3 days to be saved. AUBREY is spayed rabies, core vaccines, heartworm/tick disease tested negative for all. She is de-wormed, monthly preventatives and microchipped. At the time of rescue in the middle of January 2021, she weighed around 42.00 pounds and has an estimated date of birth 20 November 2016

. We cannot say for sure what breed she is, so we expect families to do their own research on her look and size and decide what breed you think she is and if you have the lifestyle suitable for her needs.

AUBREY arrived at the rescue in Sebec, Maine on 15th January 2021 and was very shy. This sweet girl has clearly not had a fun past, when she was scared or unsure she would sit and face away from what she was scared off, or just sit facing the wall. She is super affectionate and when she was settled and comfortable loved getting her head scratched and belly rubbed. She was in a kennel next to her best friend Carl and after a few days of making sure everyone was settled I opened the gate in the runs so that they could play together and they snuggled together too. I was hoping to adopt them together, but sadly Carl has been adopted.

After a week and most dogs getting adopted, I moved the remaining dogs in the kennel communal area where they have access to a large secure fenced in area and Aubrey and her new friends are having a great time - she still craves so desperately for attention and is the sweetest natured girl.

She deserves nothing but the best from the humans who open up their heart to her, she needs an active life, lots of adventures, exploring new places, with different sights, smells and sounds, she needs to be showered in affection and love and made to understand she will never have a horrible life where she feels she has to sit facing a wall again.

We do not know how Aubrey is around cats or livestock, however, we expect families to be prepared to adjust and work with any potential problems and ensure they can provide a safe, happy environment for everyone in the family.

More pictures and possible video's can be found on his page on the rescue website.

All dogs use dog doors to go out and do their business or to enjoy the cool, fresh weather in their dog runs or communal areas. We cannot say if a dog is house-trained, however, we expect families to understand that all dogs need a transition period and accidents could happen and training is most definitely needed.

You MUST understand that dogs need time to decompress and adapt to their new environment and home. It is a HUGE transition they make from the kill shelter, being vetted, on transport for 3 days and arriving in Maine where the temperature and such is very different to what they have only known. In rescue there is what is known as the "3 Point Rule" Days 1-3 your dog is stressed, anxious, confused as to where they are now. Weeks 1-3 your dog is adjusting, settling in, learning things. At the 3 month point, your dog understands they are home, and have built up a trusting relationship where they feel loved and secure.

All dogs are fed Rachael Ray Nutrish PEAK Natural Dry Dog Food, Grain Free Western Grasslands Recipe with Bison. Rachael Ray Nutrish Peak Dog Food receives the Dog Food Advisor's second-highest tier rating of 4.5 stars.

AUBREY is available for adoption for an adoption fee of $550

This fee is not negotiable and is used to cover the rescue costs of pulling, vetting, health certificate, transport from Texas to Maine, monthly preventatives, supplements, food, general day to day cost of running a brick and mortar rescue and anything else that is needed. Canadian adopters need to know that customs charge 15% taxes when entering into Canada.

Due to borders being closed, it is up to families to call the US and Canadian borders to find the current details on border crossing. Animal Welfare is deemed essential in the US, but quarantine rules entering back into Canada must be followed.

If you feel that you have the heart and home to give this precious soul a wonderful life, please go to our website, under the ADOPTION INFO tab, complete, then submit the APPLICATION. Our process takes around 1-2 days, and ensuring your references are aware that we will be calling, could speed up the process. Once you have been approved, we discuss any questions in regards to the dog you are wanting to adopt, then you complete and submit the contract, make payment and then we can work out the pick up / transport arrangements.

Please do NOT submit an application if you are not looking to take home a new best friend within the next few weeks.

https://www.giveadogahome-sanantonio.org/forms/form?formid=5838

ALL Dogs are LOCATED AT THE RESCUE IN SEBEC, MAINE. We post in various states along the east coast and Canada where we have had lots of successful adoptions to enable more exposure for these beautiful saved souls. Families will need to be prepared to travel to the rescue to meet and take home their new best friend. Sebec is located just outside the towns of Dover-Foxcroft and Milo (approx 8 miles) and approx 45 miles from Bangor. There are also lots of hotels, motels, pet friendly accommodations and wonderful camp-sites for the more adventurous families and what a great way to get to know your new best friend.

Click here to watch a video of AUBREY.

Hi, my name is Hope! I am a senior chihuahua who came to Buffalo Cares to find my forever home. I love napping in a warm dog bed knowing that my people are near by. I like meal time and can beg better than most dogs - as I have a cute dance that I do! My foster humans love me and have been taking great care of me. I, however, do not enjoy being home alone all day while they work so we were wondering if there is a home out there where I can be loved the rest of my days and have less time alone. I am living with another small dog and he gives me my space so we get along just fine! I do bark at the cat in the house but she is not scared of me - maybe because she is bigger! I am sweet and loving and would love to have a special home of my own. If you think I sound like the perfect girl for you, apply to adopt me today at buffalocares.org

Adoption Fee: $175 RR048

All dogs come fully up to date on shots, microchipped, heart worm tested, de-wormed, on flea and heart worm preventative, and spayed/neutered. If interested in learning more or adopting please fill out an application on our website at www.buffalocares.org.

animal.description:
Personality: Gregory is a social, smart, athletic dog that is waiting for his forever home! He can be jumpy and excitable so it's good to reward him for keeping all four paws on the floor. Gregory is a high energy dog and would make an excellent running or hiking partner. Gregory would do best in a breed experienced, adult household who can provide plenty of physical and mental exercise as well as basic training to help guide him. 

History: He came to us from another animal shelter. 

Dog/Cat Skills: Gregory can be overwhelmed and sensitive to forward, rowdy dogs. He prefers polite meets and has done well in a playgroup setting with calm, polite female dogs. He enjoys playing chase with minimal physical contact. He will correct dogs that are rude. He has a true shepherd play style and will mouth at the backs of other dogs in play and chase, and can be vocal and bossy. He has been introduced to several dogs on and off-leash, and needs appropriate, tolerant matches to be successful. We have not seen Gregory around cats. 

Leash Skills: Gregory pulls while walking on a leash and would benefit from the use of a front clipping harness.

Ready to meet Gregory ? Fill out the form to request an appointment Primary Color: Black Secondary Color: Tan Weight: 69.4lbs Age: 2yrs 2mths 1wks Animal has been Neutered

She bottle fed him and nursed him back to health, and he lived with her happily for the next 18 months.  Unfortunately she must move this month as her landlord is selling her house and she cannot take all eight of her dogs with her.  Patron needs a new home!

This big boy is 75lbs, and gets along great with all dogs and people.  He lives with cats, and can see them but not interact with them and has no interest.  Homes with cats should be prepared for a slow introduction period and constant supervision.  Patron is laid back and submissive, even at not even two years old.  He loves to play frisbee!

animal.description:
Jacob had a photoshoot to help capture his good sides. He's wondering where his forever family is and what's taking them so long to find him!

Jacob is a 1 year old shepherd mix. He is quiet and charming. I often tell my husband he should have been named Scooby Doo because of how expressive he is with his face. Jacob has lived his entire life in a shelter and therefore is timid in his foster home. He has been with us for 2.5 weeks and is slowly, but surely coming out of his shell more and more. He LOVES his foster sisters and could play with them all day in the yard. When I first brought him home, I couldn't let him off a leash because he was too afraid to approach us so it took me an hour to catch him in the yard and bring him back in. After two weeks, he met the photographer and took him only about 30-45 minutes to start taking treats from her hand.

Jacob will require an adopter who is patient and loving in order to give him the time he needs to acclimate at his own pace, but I can't tell you how loving and brave this sweet boy is. He is willing to try and trust when he has no idea what to expect and has quickly stolen my heart. If you choose to meet this beautiful boy, I'm sure he will quickly steal yours too!

We think he can see shapes if he is close enough but is getting around very well in the few days he's been in his foster home. He does have 3 different eye medications that he HAS to have twice a day. Unfortunately they are somewhat costly at around $150. Cuddles loves to, well, cuddle on the couch or roam the backyard. Cuddles would benefit from a home with minimal steps and a fenced in yard so he can roam around safely.

animal.description: Hello there, my name is Sam and I am currently seeking my perfect forever match. My best fit would be a confident and experienced human friend that can understand my past and allow me ample patience as well as help me with confidence building. I am seeking a home where I can stay safely indoors and become a part of my human's everyday life. During my stay here at HALO, I have come out of my shell to be friendly, seek attention, enjoy treats and belly rubs. It will take me time to warm up in my new home and to become accustom to the ways of the house. I would do best in one that is not very busy with visitors or guests, so that I do not become overwhelmed. I would very much like as much as benefit from having a confident, friendly, and social dog companion in my new home to help show me the ropes. Some things that I am still working on and will need continued training on after my adoption are leash acceptance training and my vocalization. A relationship of structure, routine and guidance would give me the opportunity to gain my own confidence and help me become the best boy that I can be. Please contact my friends at HALO if you are interested in meeting me.

animal.description:
Snow's family was moving and unable to take her with them. Her owners contacted us to find this beauty a Furever home. 

My name is Snow. I am a Great Pyrenees and I am sweet as can be! I have been around children, dogs, and cats and am gentle and friendly with everyone. I would love a male dog to play with in my new home. Besides being a beauty, I have a great personality too. When my foster dad greets me in the morning to go for a walk I have a special greeting for him. I bounce from one front foot to the other, my lips curl back in a smile and you can see my teeth, my tongue hangs out and I flop my head from side to side. I walk great on a leash and am house trained. I weigh about 85 lbs, will come to you spayed, up to date on vaccinations, microchipped, and up to date on flea/tick preventives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved you must pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO

animal.description:
If you're looking for the most gentle, old soul - look no further than Reno!  This 8 years young lad is an American Pit Bull Terrier.  Reno came to us weighing 122 pounds, but he  has worked hard on getting his weight down and is now a slim 89.6 pounds.   He's a calm fellow who is happiest lounging around the house while chewing on his bone.  Reno does great with other calm and gentle dogs, but a proper dog introduction is required.   

Reno has a chronic condition called panniculitis.  Panniculitis  is usually visible as a lump (in Reno's case it is a large mass on his left hip) , but it is actually inflammation of the subcutaneous fatty tissue. We treat it with an inexpensive steroid. This treatment keeps the inflammation at bay. Still it is likely that Reno will always have this condition and will occasionally have flare-ups.    

If you think Reno might be your perfect companion, apply today!  His minimum adoption fee is $195 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents.

He has been neutered, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html

animal.description:
MEET RASCAL!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4508638.

Rascal was surrendered by his owner and he doesn't know why he's at the shelter. He's doing much better than when he first came in and now he allows the staff to leash him and take him for a walk. He walks easily on the leash and he comes up and sits next to people for pets. He likes his treats and takes them nicely. His previous owner said he loves to play with soccer balls but he doesn't like small animals and will chase them. He also likes to chase garbage trucks.

Rascal is having a hard time staying in his kennel and wants to go to a home where he can play with his soccer balls in the yard. The shelter is recommending that Rascal not go to a home with children. If you think Rascal would be a good fit in your home, please come and meet him today!

If you are interested in saving this pet, please reach out via this link: https://www.shelterluv.com/matchme/foster/BPAZ/Dog

To actually visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
Age: 4
Weight: approx 70 lbs
Location: Baltimore, MD
Nicknames: Nay Nay, Penelope Primrose
Good with other dogs?: Yes.
She has not lived with dogs until coming to her foster home. She has met the dogs well.
Good with cats? unknown, will not be adopted to a home with a cat
Good with children? OK for kids over: 10
Activity Preference: Both couch potato and marathon walker. She loves to go for walks (see more on this). Loves yard activity.
IQ: Smart
Naomi's favorite things: Nomming her blankie when she sleeps. Getting pets.
Naomi is good at: meeting people, meeting dogs, behaving in the house, going for car rides, playing with toys gently
Ideal home: a fenced yard because this girl needs to run!
Training Needs: Leash walking needs to improve.
Health issues: Needs grain free diet for allergies

Meet Naomi

Whoever opens their home to Naomi will have a companion for life. She loves being nearby and, occasionally, on your lap (partially). She gives kisses and sweet love looks. She looks like she is mean mugging all the time but what's behind that adorable face is anything but mean. She's a hazel-eyed beauty with the cutest underbite and brown-blonde brindle and freckles.

In a matter of weeks, Nay Nay has endeared herself to her foster mom mostly through her impeccable house manners and from the loving trust she readily shows. She listens well and learns quickly. Counter surfing? Barking lots? Getting into trash? Ripping up things? Accidents in the house? Not with this girl. She's well behaved, respectful to people and dogs, loves toys but doesn't destroy them, leaves things alone that aren't hers, and is expert level at house training.

There are some things you must be prepared for to give Naomi her best life:

Time to wake up. This girl is not an early riser and doesn't like getting out of bed, especially if it's a people bed that's oh so comfy. She pretty much needs some a good petting before she wants to start the day.
A bathroom companion. She realizes that when you're on the toilet, she has a captive audience. So forget about reading or using your phone. Those hands of yours are meant for petting, so get to it!
An invitation to eat. Yep, that's right, she seems to need an invitation to eat from her bowl. She stays off to the side as her meal is prepped and will stay away until she gets the go ahead. Oh, and she is not a big fan of just dry food. Broth, pumpkin, wet food. Just something to take the edge off.
Permission to get on furniture. She really does love being with you on the couch and even fancies herself a bit of a lap dog at times but she must be asked to join you. She's a good bed buddy. She'll settle in by your feet and barely move throughout the night. No taking over the bed like some other rude dogs I know.

There are some other specifics we'll be looking at for her forever family. That includes a fenced yard because this girl loves to run. Also, Nay needs to be on a grain free diet. Her former owner said Nay has a grain allergy and sensitive stomach. She's being transitioned back to a grain free food and so far there have been no indications of problems.

Lastly, she needs someone who will commit to working with her on her leash walking. She is a puller but she absolutely loves going for a walk. We're working on both enjoying the walk. She's getting better but it's taking time.

Other than a few weeks at her foster home, Naomi has not lived with dogs. She is a bit socially awkward meeting other dogs. She gets so excited she wants to rush in and happily say hello. She's working on toning that down some. She wants to play with other dogs but the resident pups here are playing hard to get. I think she would love to live with another dog, as long as that dog isn't sensitive to her exuberance.

As for kids, her former owner said Naomi would be fine living with them. Based on my experience with her, I would say older kids would be better because Naomi likes to jump around when she gets excited. She has not jumped on me, but I could see her knocking over smaller kids even though she wouldn't intend to.

I hope that, after reading this, you see what a wonderful dog she is. She will make any one happy. If you think you can offer what she needs to be happy, please apply today.

PLEASE READ: Adopters will not be considered without completing an application. Please visit www.AmericanBulldogRescue.org to apply! Remember - Adoption is always the best option! If you can't help by adopting a homeless pet, please consider making a tax-deductible donation to American Bulldog Rescue, 4 Terry Drive, Suite 1D Newtown, PA 18940 or paypal AmericanBulldogRescue@verizon.net. We cannot place dogs in homes with children under 10 unless that dog has lived with kids or is in a foster home with kids. Thank you.
To be considered for adoption, you must apply using our free, online application. Our dogs are fostered in our volunteers' homes, not in a central shelter/location. Only approved applicants are put into contact with the foster family to setup a meeting with the foster dog. Visit our Adoption Policies web page for more information and a link to our application: http://americanbulldogrescue.org/adoption-policies/.

animal.description:
This pretty lady is Mama Baker! She is a ~3 year old mixed breed who weighs about 60 pounds.  When she first came to us, she had a belly full of puppies.  They all found their forever homes and Mama Baker is still eager to find her pawfect match!

Mama Baker is sweet as pie, but she is also very timid at first. She'll need an adopter who will go slow and be patient with her while she adjusts to her new surroundings - new situations can be scary for a timid gal like her. An experienced dog owner who is willing to work with her on her fear would be ideal.  Once she warms up and realizes she's safe and loved, she will love you unconditionally.  Mama Baker is very gentle and loves to snuggle and lay her head on her person's lap. Keep in mind that her unconditional love can also lead her to be protective of her people.  For this reason, she needs a home with no other dogs.  It will also be necessary for her new family to let her hangout in another room if there are visitors. 

Mama Baker prefers to hangout with adults and warms up to them much quicker than children, so she kindly requests no kids under the age of 16 in her forever family.  As with any visitor, if you have children that visit or neighborhood kids, Mama Baker would feel much safer and more comfortable if you let her hang out in another room.  A secure fence is a requirement to adopt Mama Baker.

If you can provide Mama Baker with the home environment she's looking for, apply to adopt today!  Her minimum adoption fee is $235 plus a $12 fee, if 4 months or older, for rabies registration for McLean County residents.

She has been spayed, microchipped, vaccinated, heartworm checked, dewormed, and is on flea and heartworm preventatives.

For information about this dog's breed(s), visit: http://www.dogbreedinfo.com/abc.htm 

To fill out our adoption application, go to: http://fs16.formsite.com/WishBoneCanineRescue/adoptionapplication/index.html
